s to the corrido and a translation into English.\n\n{{Mexican-American}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cortez, Gregorio}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:American folklore]]\n[[Category:American outlaws]]\n[[Category:Mexican emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Matamoros, Tamaulipas]]\n[[Category:American people of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:People from Travis County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n", "name_user": "Chr66", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSupporters:some instead of many anglo support", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregorio_Cortez"}
{"title_page": "Francis Townsend", "text_new": "{{about|the old-age pension advocate|the U.S. Homeland Security advisor|Frances Townsend}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Francis Townsend\n| image         = Francis Townsend, seated at desk, with microphones hec.27728.jpg\n| alt           = Francis Townsend, seated at desk, with microphones, c. 1939\n| caption       = Townsend c. 1939\n| birth_name    = Francis Everett Townsend\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1867|01|13}}\n| birth_place   = [[Fairbury, Illinois]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1960|09|01|1867|01|13}}\n| death_place   = [[Los Angeles]]\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Omaha Medical College]]\n| occupation    = [[Physician]], [[public health]] officer\n| known_for     = Townsend Plan\n| spouse        = Wilhelmina \"Minnie\" Bogue\n}}\n'''Francis Everett Townsend''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|a\u028a|n|z|\u0259n|d}}; January 13, 1867 \u2013 September 1, 1960) was an [[United States|American]] [[physician]] who was best known for his revolving old-age [[pension]] proposal during the [[Great Depression]].  Known as the \"Townsend Plan\", this proposal influenced the establishment of the [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Roosevelt administration]]'s [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] system.  He was born just outside [[Fairbury, Illinois]], where he is memorialized by a post office named in his honor.\n\n==Life and career==\nFrancis Everett Townsend was born the second of six children on January 13, 1867, in Fairbury, Illinois.<ref name=\"When\">{{cite book |title=When Movements Matter: The Townsend Plan and the Rise of Social Security |last=Amenta|first=Edwin|authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2006|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |location= |isbn=0691124736|pages=36\u201338|accessdate=May 26, 2012 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AN5QukE1Qi0C&pg=PA39&dq=%22Midway+City%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Yme-T4iiOamZiQLTidzFDQ&ved=0CFsQ6AEwBjgy#v=onepage&q=%22Midway%20City&f=false}}</ref> After Townsend contracted [[swamp malaria]] as an infant, the Townsend family moved to [[Nebraska]] where Townsend had two years of high school education.<ref name=\"When\"/> In 1898, Townsend borrowed $1,000 from his father and moved to [[Southern California]] to develop a [[hay|hay farming]] business.<ref name=\"When\"/> The business was not successful, and Townsend enrolled in [[Omaha Medical College]] when he was 31.<ref name=\"When\"/> After graduating, Townsend worked in the medical field in [[Belle Fourche, South Dakota]], and met a nurse and his future wife, Wilhelmina \"Minnie\" Bogue.<ref name=\"When\"/> At age 50, Townsend enlisted as a doctor in the army one year before the end of [[World War I]].<ref name=\"When\"/>\n\nAfter the war ended in 1918, Townsend moved to [[Long Beach, California]], to run a dry ice factory.<ref name=\"When\"/> After that business quickly failed, Townsend worked for [[real estate agent]] Robert Earl Clements in [[Midway City, California]].<ref name=\"When\"/> Clements later masterminded the Townsend Plan.<ref name=\"When\"/> In 1930, at the start of the [[Great Depression]], Townsend became a Long Beach city [[public health|public health officer]] at age 63, but lost his job three years later.<ref name=\"When\"/>\n\nTownsend died in [[Los Angeles]] on September 1, 1960.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Dr. Francis Townsend, 93, Dies; Founded Old-Age Pension Plan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/09/02/archives/dr-townsend-dies-led-oldage-plan-dr-francis-townsend93-dies-founded.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York |date=September 2, 1960 |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |access-date=January 19, 2019 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==The Townsend Plan==\nThe Townsend Plan proposed that every person over 60 be paid $200 per month. The Old-Age Revolving Pension fund was to be supported by a 2% national sales tax.<ref name=\"Scheme\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ssa.gov/history/towns5.html |title=Research Note #17: The Townsend Plan's Pension Scheme |work=Research Notes & Special Studies by the Historian's Office, Social Security Administration |author=Larry Dewitt |date=December 2001 |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThere were three requirements for beneficiaries under the Plan:\n\n* they had to be retired;\n* they had to be \"free from habitual criminality;\"\n* they had to spend the money within 30 days (to stimulate the economy.)<ref name=\"Scheme\"/>\n\n===Promoting the plan===\n[[Image:TownsendF2.jpg|right|thumb|Townsend talks with Senator [[Sheridan Downey]]]]\nIn September 1933, Townsend wrote a letter to the editor of the local newspaper (the ''[[Long Beach Press-Telegram]]'')<ref>{{cite web |url=https://psmag.com/social-justice/frustrated-blogger-made-expanding-social-security-respectable-idea-67226 |title=How a Frustrated Blogger Made Expanding Social Security a Respectable Idea |author=David Dayen |date=October 29, 2013 |work=Pacific Standard |accessdate=January 13, 2014}}</ref>, and launched his career as an old-age activist.<ref name=\"When\"/> According to Townsend's autobiographical memoir, ''New Horizons'' (1943), his plan originated when he looked out his window one morning in the early depth of the Depression and saw two old women, dressed in once nice, now tattered clothes, picking through his garbage cans looking for food.  Within two years of his putting forward his plan, over 3400 Townsend Plan Clubs were organized all over America, and began exerting pressure on Congress to pass an old age pension.  [[Frances Perkins]], President Roosevelt's Secretary of Labor, in her memoir, ''The Roosevelt I Knew'' (p. 294) says that Roosevelt told her, \"We have to have it [Social Security]. Congress can't stand the pressure of the Townsend Plan unless we have a real old-age insurance system.\"  As Roosevelt said, Social Security was passed by Congress substituting a pay-as-you-go \"insurance\" scheme for Townsend's far more generous pension plan, but as he told Perkins, it was the Townsend Clubs that forced Congress to act at all.\n\n===After the adoption of Social Security and Townsend's death===\nThe movement continued after the Roosevelt administration adopted Social Security in 1935 and beyond Townsend's death in 1960.<ref name=\"plandeath\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Townsend Plan, Once the Hope Of Thousands, Is Near Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/02/23/archives/townsend-plan-once-the-hope-of-thousands-is-near-death.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York |date=February 23, 1978 |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |access-date=January 19, 2019}}</ref> In 1978, [[The Associated Press]] reported that the National Townsend Plan would be shut down by the end of February that year, with only state chapters surviving, and that by then it had a \"dwindling and aging membership.\"<ref name=\"plandeath\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Francis Townsend}}\n* US Social Security Administration, [https://www.ssa.gov/history/towns5.html \"The Townsend Plan Movement,\"] ''Social Security History.''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Townsend, Francis}}\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1936 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Belle Fourche, South Dakota]]\n[[Category:American political party founders]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the old-age pension advocate|the U.S. Homeland Security advisor|Frances Townsend}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Francis Townsend\n| image         = Francis Townsend, seated at desk, with microphones hec.27728.jpg\n| alt           = Francis Townsend, seated at desk, with microphones, c. 1939\n| caption       = Townsend c. 1939\n| birth_name    = Francis Everett Townsend\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1867|01|13}}\n| birth_place   = [[Fairbury, Illinois]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1960|09|01|1867|01|13}}\n| death_place   = [[Los Angeles]]\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Omaha Medical College]]\n| occupation    = [[Physician]], [[public health]] officer\n| known_for     = Townsend Plan\n| spouse        = Wilhelmina \"Minnie\" Bogue\n}}\n'''Francis Everett Townsend''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|a\u028a|n|z|\u0259n|d}}; January 13, 1867 \u2013 September 1, 1960) was an [[United States|American]] [[physician]] who was best known for his revolving old-age [[pension]] proposal during the [[Great Depression]].  Known as the \"Townsend Plan\", this proposal influenced the establishment of the [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Roosevelt administration]]'s [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] system.  He was born just outside [[Fairbury, Illinois]], where he is memorialized by a post office named in his honor.\n\n==Life and career==\nFrancis Everett Townsend was born the second of six children on January 13, 1867, in Fairbury, Illinois.<ref name=\"When\">{{cite book |title=When Movements Matter: The Townsend Plan and the Rise of Social Security |last=Amenta|first=Edwin|authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2006|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |location= |isbn=0691124736|pages=36\u201338|accessdate=May 26, 2012 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AN5QukE1Qi0C&pg=PA39&dq=%22Midway+City%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Yme-T4iiOamZiQLTidzFDQ&ved=0CFsQ6AEwBjgy#v=onepage&q=%22Midway%20City&f=false}}</ref> After Townsend contracted [[swamp malaria]] as an infant, the Townsend family moved to [[Nebraska]] where Townsend had two years of high school education.<ref name=\"When\"/> In 1898, Townsend borrowed $1,000 from his father and moved to [[Southern California]] to develop a [[hay|hay farming]] business.<ref name=\"When\"/> The business was not successful, and Townsend enrolled in [[Omaha Medical College]] when he was 31.<ref name=\"When\"/> After graduating, Townsend worked in the medical field in [[Belle Fourche, South Dakota]], and met a nurse and his future wife, Wilhelmina \"Minnie\" Bogue.<ref name=\"When\"/> At age 50, Townsend enlisted as a doctor in the army one year before the end of [[World War I]].<ref name=\"When\"/>\n\nAfter the war ended in 1918, Townsend moved to [[Long Beach, California]], to run a dry ice factory.<ref name=\"When\"/> After that business quickly failed, Townsend worked for [[real estate agent]] Robert Earl Clements in [[Midway City, California]].<ref name=\"When\"/> Clements later masterminded the Townsend Plan.<ref name=\"When\"/> In 1930, at the start of the [[Great Depression]], Townsend became a Long Beach city [[public health|public health officer]] at age 63, but lost his job three years later.<ref name=\"When\"/>\n\nTownsend died in [[Los Angeles]] on September 1, 1960.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Dr. Francis Townsend, 93, Dies; Founded Old-Age Pension Plan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/09/02/archives/dr-townsend-dies-led-oldage-plan-dr-francis-townsend93-dies-founded.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York |date=September 2, 1960 |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |access-date=January 19, 2019 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==The Townsend Plan==\nThe Townsend Plan proposed that every person over 60 be paid $200 per month. The Old-Age Revolving Pension fund was to be supported by a 2% national sales tax.<ref name=\"Scheme\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ssa.gov/history/towns5.html |title=Research Note #17: The Townsend Plan's Pension Scheme |work=Research Notes & Special Studies by the Historian's Office, Social Security Administration |author=Larry Dewitt |date=December 2001 |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThere were three requirements for beneficiaries under the Plan:\n\n* they had to be retired;\n* they had to be \"free from habitual criminality;\"\n* they had to spend the money within 30 days (to stimulate the economy.)<ref name=\"Scheme\"/>\n\n===Promoting the plan===\n[[Image:TownsendF2.jpg|right|thumb|Townsend talks with Senator [[Sheridan Downey]]]]\nIn September 1933, Townsend wrote a letter to the editor of the local newspaper (the ''[[Long Beach Press-Telegram]]'')<ref>{{cite web |url=https://psmag.com/social-justice/frustrated-blogger-made-expanding-social-security-respectable-idea-67226 |title=How a Frustrated Blogger Made Expanding Social Security a Respectable Idea |author=David Dayen |date=October 29, 2013 |work=Pacific Standard |accessdate=January 13, 2014}}</ref>, and launched his career as an old-age activist.<ref name=\"When\"/> According to Townsend's autobiographical memoir, ''New Horizons'' (1943), his plan originated when he looked out his window one morning in the early depth of the Depression and saw two old women, dressed in once nice, now tattered clothes, picking through his garbage cans looking for food.  Within two years of his putting forward his plan, over 3400 Townsend Plan Clubs were organized all over America, and began exerting pressure on Congress to pass an old age pension.  [[Frances Perkins]], President Roosevelt's Secretary of Labor, in her memoir, ''The Roosevelt I Knew'' (p. 294) says that Roosevelt told her, \"We have to have it [Social Security]. Congress can't stand the pressure of the Townsend Plan unless we have a real old-age insurance system.\"  As Roosevelt said, Social Security was passed by Congress substituting a pay-as-you-go \"insurance\" scheme for Townsend's far more generous pension plan, but as he told Perkins, it was the Townsend Clubs that forced Congress to act at all.\n\n===After the adoption of Social Security and Townsend's death===\nThe movement continued after the Roosevelt administration adopted Social Security in 1935 and beyond Townsend's death in 1960.<ref name=\"plandeath\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Townsend Plan, Once the Hope Of Thousands, Is Near Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/02/23/archives/townsend-plan-once-the-hope-of-thousands-is-near-death.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York |date=February 23, 1978 |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |access-date=January 19, 2019}}</ref> In 1978, [[The Associated Press]] reported that the National Townsend Plan would be shut down by the end of February that year, with only state chapters surviving, and that by then it had a \"dwindling and aging membership\".<ref name=\"plandeath\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Francis Townsend}}\n* US Social Security Administration, [https://www.ssa.gov/history/towns5.html \"The Townsend Plan Movement,\"] ''Social Security History.''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Townsend, Francis}}\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1936 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Belle Fourche, South Dakota]]\n[[Category:American political party founders]]\n", "name_user": "Sherlock1895", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAfter the adoption of Social Security and Townsend's death:punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Townsend"}
{"title_page": "Hatfield, Massachusetts", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Hatfield, Massachusetts\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = Industry, Prosperity\n|image_skyline            = Hatfield Memorial Town Hall, MA.jpg\n|imagesize                = 250px\n|image_caption            = Hatfield Memorial Town Hall\n|image_seal               = HatfieldMA-seal.png\n|image_flag               = \n|image_map                = Hatfield_ma_highlight.png\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location in Hampshire County in Massachusetts\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Massachusetts]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Massachusetts|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire]]\n|established_title        = Settled\n|established_date         = 1661\n|established_title2       = Incorporated\n|established_date2        = 1670\n|established_title3       = \n|established_date3        = \n|government_type          = [[Open town meeting]]\n|leader_title             = <!--[[Town Administrator|Town<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Administrator]]-->\n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = <!--Board of <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Selectmen-->\n|leader_name1             = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 43.6\n|area_total_sq_mi         = \n|area_land_km2            = 41.2\n|area_land_sq_mi          = \n|area_water_km2           = 2.4\n|area_water_sq_mi         = \n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|settlement_type          = [[New England town|Town]]\n|population_total         = 3279\n|population_density_km2   = 79.6\n|population_density_sq_mi = \n|elevation_m              = 39\n|elevation_ft             = 129\n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Standard Time Zone|Eastern]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = [[Eastern Standard Time Zone|Eastern]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|coordinates              = {{coord|42|22|15|N|72|35|55|W|region:US-MA|display=inline,title}}\n|website                  = {{URL|www.townofhatfield.org}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP Code]]s\n|postal_code              = 01038, 01088, 01066\n|area_code                = [[Area code 413|413]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 25-29265\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0618202\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Hatfield''' is a [[New England town|town]] in [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire County]], [[Massachusetts]], United States. The population was 3,279 at the 2010 census.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0600000US2501529265| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001): Hatfield town, Hampshire County, Massachusetts| work=American Factfinder| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| accessdate=August 8, 2017| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213155829/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0600000US2501529265| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> It is part of the [[Springfield, Massachusetts]] [[Springfield metropolitan area, Massachusetts|Metropolitan Statistical Area]]. The [[census-designated place]] of [[Hatfield (CDP), Massachusetts|Hatfield]] consists of the town center and surrounding areas.\n\n==History==\n{{More citations needed section|date=March 2018}}\n[[File:Cornelia Billings House Hatfield Massachusetts.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Cornelia Billings House, Hatfield]]\nHatfield was founded in 1660 on land granted to General [[Daniel Dennison]] and Governor [[William Bradford (Plymouth Colony governor)|William Bradford]]. It was formally incorporated as a town in 1670 and has a [[board of selectmen]] and an annual [[town meeting]].\n\nOne of the theories of Hatfield's incorporation in 1670 was that during that time it was a colony of Hadley and Hadley's church was located across the [[Connecticut River]] on what's now West Street in present day [[Hadley, Massachusetts|Hadley]]. The citizens living in what is now Hatfield asked the officials if they could build the church on this side of the river, so that they can go to church and not have to cross the river, which was hard to cross every week, especially during the winter season when the river would freeze. When the citizens asked main Hadley, Hadley said \"No.\" Enraged, they held a vote on whether Hatfield would still remain territory of Hadley, or secede into its own town. The vote for seceding won. Many believed this was a good decision as during that time, travel wasn't easy, and it was very unusual for the already large Hadley which had already claimed many of its surrounding towns to have a spot on the other side of the river.\n\nAs a center for agriculture the region produced cattle, sheep, corn, and tobacco. At first their relations with the local Native Americans were very welcoming on both sides. On October 16, 1675, a substantial part of the town was destroyed in [[King Philip's War]], and surviving settlers sought refuge in [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]]. On September 19, 1677, another raid occurred, killing thirteen.\n\nDuring the [[American Revolution]], Hatfield was an important source of supplies and men for the rebels. In 1786 the town was used as an assembly area for the discontented who became involved in [[Shays' Rebellion]].\n\nOne family supplied many of Hatfield's physicians for generations. The Hastings family, descendants of [[England|English]] [[Puritan]] immigrant [[Thomas Hastings (colonist)|Thomas Hastings]], was originally settled at [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]], but within a generation members of the family had relocated to Hatfield, where they produced a succession of Hatfield physicians, including Dr. Thomas Hastings (1652&ndash;1712); Dr. Thomas Hastings (1679&ndash;1728); Dr. Waitstill Hastings (1714&ndash;1748); and Dr. John Hastings (1765&ndash;1845).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=8w0WAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA417&lpg=PA417&dq=%22the+hastings+family%22+watertown+physician+a+history+of+hatfield+massachusetts&source=bl&ots=QGLam1B4_t&sig=BZjDE-JcqpORhOrZ2_AIASIzyLw&hl=en&ei=aYzES9HbO4WssgO3n7n8DA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CAgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false Daniel White Wells, Reuben Field Wells, ''A History of Hatfield, Massachusetts, in Three Parts'', published by F. C. H. Gibbons, Springfield, Massachusetts, 1910]</ref> The first Thomas Hastings, aside from serving as physician to Hatfield and surrounding communities, was also the town's first schoolteacher.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7CiNs31KULoC&pg=PA30&sig=BOea_thXT6UjlTzrhT7KW_PCBAM&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Herbert B. Adams: Tributes of Friends, with a Bibliography of the Department of History, Politics and Economics of the Johns Hopkins University'', Johns Hopkins Press, Baltimore, 1902]</ref> He authored a contemporary account of the devastating Indian attack on nearby [[Deerfield, Massachusetts|Deerfield]] in 1704.\n\nHatfield was the birthplace and hometown of [[Sophia Smith]] (1796\u20131870), the founder of both Smith Academy (the Hatfield public high school), and [[Smith College]], the famous women's college in [[Northampton, Massachusetts|Northampton]]. Another notable resident was [[Rebecca Dickinson]] (1738\u20131812), a never-married gownmaker whose surviving diary, preserved in the collections of the Pocumtuck Valley Memorial Association in Deerfield, has served as the basis for scholarship in early American women's history.<ref>Works include {{cite book |last1=Miller |first1=Marla |title=Rebecca Dickinson: Independence for a New England Woman |date=2013 |publisher=Westview Press |location=Boulder, CO |isbn=9780813347660}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nHatfield is located on the west bank of the [[Connecticut River]] at the mouth of the Mill River, {{convert|25|mi}} north of [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]] and about {{convert|100|mi|-1}} west of [[Boston]]. It is bordered to the west by Horse Mountain (a typical New England granite glacial remnant) and the town of [[Williamsburg, Massachusetts|Williamsburg]], to the north by the town of [[Whately, Massachusetts|Whately]], to the east and south across the Connecticut River by the town of [[Hadley, Massachusetts|Hadley]], and to the southwest by the city of [[Northampton, Massachusetts|Northampton]]. The village of Hatfield is in the southern part of the town, next to the Connecticut River, while the villages of Westbrook, North Hatfield, and Bradstreet are near the northern border. West Hatfield is in the southwest part of town, next to the Northampton border.\n\n[[U.S. Route 5]]/[[Massachusetts Route 10|Route 10]] and [[Interstate 91]] pass through the town, with access to I-91 from Exits 21 and 22, where it intersects with US 5/Route 10. The village of Hatfield is about {{convert|2|mi|0}} east of Routes 5 and 91.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town of Hatfield has a total area of {{convert|43.6|sqkm|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|41.2|sqkm|order=flip}} are land and {{convert|2.4|sqkm|order=flip}}, or 5.51%, are water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations | type=USA | align=left | state=collapsed\n | 1850|1073\n | 1860|1337\n | 1870|1594\n | 1880|1495\n | 1890|1246\n | 1900|1500\n | 1910|1986\n | 1920|2651\n | 1930|2476\n | 1940|2216\n | 1950|2179\n | 1960|2350\n | 1970|2825\n | 1980|3045\n | 1990|3184\n | 2000|3249\n | 2010|3279\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 3,249 people, 1,381 households, and 871 families residing in the town.  The [[population density]] was 202.8 people per square mile (78.3/km\u00b2).  There were 1,431 housing units at an average density of 89.3 per square mile (34.5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the town was 98.03% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.22% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.12% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.49% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.06% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.58% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.49% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.05% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,381 households out of which 27.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.1% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 36.9% were non-families. 29.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.35 and the average family size was 2.96.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 20.7% under the age of 18, 5.4% from 18 to 24, 27.2% from 25 to 44, 29.9% from 45 to 64, and 16.7% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females, there were 95.0 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 90.7 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $50,238, and the median income for a family was $61,607. Males had a median income of $39,414 versus $35,042 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $24,813.  About 1.4% of families and 2.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 1.2% of those under age 18 and 6.1% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==School system==\nHatfield has two public schools: an elementary school and a high school. Hatfield Elementary school ranges from grades pre-K to 6. The high school, [[Smith Academy]], is grades 7\u201312; with just over 190 students, it is the smallest public school in the state of Massachusetts.\n\n==Points of interest==\n* [[Borden Base Line]]\n* [[Mill-Prospect Street Historic District]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.townofhatfield.org/ Town of Hatfield official website]\n* [http://www.mainstreetmaps.com/MA/Hatfield/ Town of Hatfield official GIS maps and online property information] \n* [http://hatfieldhistory.weebly.com/ Hatfield Historical Society]\n* [http://www.hatfieldbusiness.org/ Hatfield Business Association]\n\n{{Hampshire County, Massachusetts}}\n{{Connecticut River}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Hampshire County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 1660s]]\n[[Category:Springfield metropolitan area, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Connecticut River]]\n[[Category:Towns in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Hatfield, Massachusetts| ]]\n[[Category:1661 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Hatfield, Massachusetts\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = Industry, prosperity\n|image_skyline            = Hatfield Memorial Town Hall, MA.jpg\n|imagesize                = 250px\n|image_caption            = Hatfield Memorial Town Hall\n|image_seal               = HatfieldMA-seal.png\n|image_flag               = \n|image_map                = Hatfield_ma_highlight.png\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location in Hampshire County in Massachusetts\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Massachusetts]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Massachusetts|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire]]\n|established_title        = Settled\n|established_date         = 1661\n|established_title2       = Incorporated\n|established_date2        = 1670\n|established_title3       = \n|established_date3        = \n|government_type          = [[Open town meeting]]\n|leader_title             = <!--[[Town Administrator|Town<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Administrator]]-->\n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = <!--Board of <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Selectmen-->\n|leader_name1             = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 43.6\n|area_total_sq_mi         = \n|area_land_km2            = 41.2\n|area_land_sq_mi          = \n|area_water_km2           = 2.4\n|area_water_sq_mi         = \n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|settlement_type          = [[New England town|Town]]\n|population_total         = 3279\n|population_density_km2   = 79.6\n|population_density_sq_mi = \n|elevation_m              = 39\n|elevation_ft             = 129\n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Standard Time Zone|Eastern]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = [[Eastern Standard Time Zone|Eastern]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|coordinates              = {{coord|42|22|15|N|72|35|55|W|region:US-MA|display=inline,title}}\n|website                  = {{URL|www.townofhatfield.org}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP Code]]s\n|postal_code              = 01038, 01088, 01066\n|area_code                = [[Area code 413|413]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 25-29265\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0618202\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Hatfield''' is a [[New England town|town]] in [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire County]], [[Massachusetts]], United States. The population was 3,279 at the 2010 census.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0600000US2501529265| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001): Hatfield town, Hampshire County, Massachusetts| work=American Factfinder| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| accessdate=August 8, 2017| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213155829/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0600000US2501529265| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> It is part of the [[Springfield, Massachusetts]] [[Springfield metropolitan area, Massachusetts|Metropolitan Statistical Area]]. The [[census-designated place]] of [[Hatfield (CDP), Massachusetts|Hatfield]] consists of the town center and surrounding areas.\n\n==History==\n{{More citations needed section|date=March 2018}}\n[[File:Cornelia Billings House Hatfield Massachusetts.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Cornelia Billings House, Hatfield]]\nHatfield was founded in 1660 on land granted to General [[Daniel Dennison]] and Governor [[William Bradford (Plymouth Colony governor)|William Bradford]]. It was formally incorporated as a town in 1670 and has a [[board of selectmen]] and an annual [[town meeting]].\n\nOne of the theories of Hatfield's incorporation in 1670 was that during that time it was a colony of Hadley and Hadley's church was located across the [[Connecticut River]] on what's now West Street in present day [[Hadley, Massachusetts|Hadley]]. The citizens living in what is now Hatfield asked the officials if they could build the church on this side of the river, so that they can go to church and not have to cross the river, which was hard to cross every week, especially during the winter season when the river would freeze. When the citizens asked main Hadley, Hadley said \"No.\" Enraged, they held a vote on whether Hatfield would still remain territory of Hadley, or secede into its own town. The vote for seceding won. Many believed this was a good decision as during that time, travel wasn't easy, and it was very unusual for the already large Hadley which had already claimed many of its surrounding towns to have a spot on the other side of the river.\n\nAs a center for agriculture the region produced cattle, sheep, corn, and tobacco. At first their relations with the local Native Americans were very welcoming on both sides. On October 16, 1675, a substantial part of the town was destroyed in [[King Philip's War]], and surviving settlers sought refuge in [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]]. On September 19, 1677, another raid occurred, killing thirteen.\n\nDuring the [[American Revolution]], Hatfield was an important source of supplies and men for the rebels. In 1786 the town was used as an assembly area for the discontented who became involved in [[Shays' Rebellion]].\n\nOne family supplied many of Hatfield's physicians for generations. The Hastings family, descendants of [[England|English]] [[Puritan]] immigrant [[Thomas Hastings (colonist)|Thomas Hastings]], was originally settled at [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]], but within a generation members of the family had relocated to Hatfield, where they produced a succession of Hatfield physicians, including Dr. Thomas Hastings (1652&ndash;1712); Dr. Thomas Hastings (1679&ndash;1728); Dr. Waitstill Hastings (1714&ndash;1748); and Dr. John Hastings (1765&ndash;1845).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=8w0WAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA417&lpg=PA417&dq=%22the+hastings+family%22+watertown+physician+a+history+of+hatfield+massachusetts&source=bl&ots=QGLam1B4_t&sig=BZjDE-JcqpORhOrZ2_AIASIzyLw&hl=en&ei=aYzES9HbO4WssgO3n7n8DA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CAgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false Daniel White Wells, Reuben Field Wells, ''A History of Hatfield, Massachusetts, in Three Parts'', published by F. C. H. Gibbons, Springfield, Massachusetts, 1910]</ref> The first Thomas Hastings, aside from serving as physician to Hatfield and surrounding communities, was also the town's first schoolteacher.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7CiNs31KULoC&pg=PA30&sig=BOea_thXT6UjlTzrhT7KW_PCBAM&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Herbert B. Adams: Tributes of Friends, with a Bibliography of the Department of History, Politics and Economics of the Johns Hopkins University'', Johns Hopkins Press, Baltimore, 1902]</ref> He authored a contemporary account of the devastating Indian attack on nearby [[Deerfield, Massachusetts|Deerfield]] in 1704.\n\nHatfield was the birthplace and hometown of [[Sophia Smith]] (1796\u20131870), the founder of both Smith Academy (the Hatfield public high school), and [[Smith College]], the famous women's college in [[Northampton, Massachusetts|Northampton]]. Another notable resident was [[Rebecca Dickinson]] (1738\u20131812), a never-married gownmaker whose surviving diary, preserved in the collections of the Pocumtuck Valley Memorial Association in Deerfield, has served as the basis for scholarship in early American women's history.<ref>Works include {{cite book |last1=Miller |first1=Marla |title=Rebecca Dickinson: Independence for a New England Woman |date=2013 |publisher=Westview Press |location=Boulder, CO |isbn=9780813347660}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nHatfield is located on the west bank of the [[Connecticut River]] at the mouth of the Mill River, {{convert|25|mi}} north of [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]] and about {{convert|100|mi|-1}} west of [[Boston]]. It is bordered to the west by Horse Mountain (a typical New England granite glacial remnant) and the town of [[Williamsburg, Massachusetts|Williamsburg]], to the north by the town of [[Whately, Massachusetts|Whately]], to the east and south across the Connecticut River by the town of [[Hadley, Massachusetts|Hadley]], and to the southwest by the city of [[Northampton, Massachusetts|Northampton]]. The village of Hatfield is in the southern part of the town, next to the Connecticut River, while the villages of Westbrook, North Hatfield, and Bradstreet are near the northern border. West Hatfield is in the southwest part of town, next to the Northampton border.\n\n[[U.S. Route 5]]/[[Massachusetts Route 10|Route 10]] and [[Interstate 91]] pass through the town, with access to I-91 from Exits 21 and 22, where it intersects with US 5/Route 10. The village of Hatfield is about {{convert|2|mi|0}} east of Routes 5 and 91.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town of Hatfield has a total area of {{convert|43.6|sqkm|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|41.2|sqkm|order=flip}} are land and {{convert|2.4|sqkm|order=flip}}, or 5.51%, are water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations | type=USA | align=left | state=collapsed\n | 1850|1073\n | 1860|1337\n | 1870|1594\n | 1880|1495\n | 1890|1246\n | 1900|1500\n | 1910|1986\n | 1920|2651\n | 1930|2476\n | 1940|2216\n | 1950|2179\n | 1960|2350\n | 1970|2825\n | 1980|3045\n | 1990|3184\n | 2000|3249\n | 2010|3279\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 3,249 people, 1,381 households, and 871 families residing in the town.  The [[population density]] was 202.8 people per square mile (78.3/km\u00b2).  There were 1,431 housing units at an average density of 89.3 per square mile (34.5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the town was 98.03% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.22% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.12% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.49% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.06% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.58% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.49% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.05% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,381 households out of which 27.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.1% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 36.9% were non-families. 29.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.35 and the average family size was 2.96.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 20.7% under the age of 18, 5.4% from 18 to 24, 27.2% from 25 to 44, 29.9% from 45 to 64, and 16.7% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females, there were 95.0 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 90.7 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $50,238, and the median income for a family was $61,607. Males had a median income of $39,414 versus $35,042 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $24,813.  About 1.4% of families and 2.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 1.2% of those under age 18 and 6.1% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==School system==\nHatfield has two public schools: an elementary school and a high school. Hatfield Elementary school ranges from grades pre-K to 6. The high school, [[Smith Academy]], is grades 7\u201312; with just over 190 students, it is the smallest public school in the state of Massachusetts.\n\n==Points of interest==\n* [[Borden Base Line]]\n* [[Mill-Prospect Street Historic District]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.townofhatfield.org/ Town of Hatfield official website]\n* [http://www.mainstreetmaps.com/MA/Hatfield/ Town of Hatfield official GIS maps and online property information] \n* [http://hatfieldhistory.weebly.com/ Hatfield Historical Society]\n* [http://www.hatfieldbusiness.org/ Hatfield Business Association]\n\n{{Hampshire County, Massachusetts}}\n{{Connecticut River}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Hampshire County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 1660s]]\n[[Category:Springfield metropolitan area, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Connecticut River]]\n[[Category:Towns in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Hatfield, Massachusetts| ]]\n[[Category:1661 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Simtropolitan", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hatfield,_Massachusetts"}
{"title_page": "Fay Weldon", "text_new": "{{short description|English author, essayist and playwright}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[FRSL]] \n| name = Fay Weldon\n| image = Fay-Weldon Copenhagen-2008.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Weldon at the 2008 Copenhagen Book Fair\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1931|9|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist |\n* {{marriage|Ronald Bateman|1957|1959|end=div}}\n* {{marriage|Ron Weldon|1963|1994|end=d.}}\n* {{marriage|Nick Fox|1994}}\n}}\n| children           = Nicolas (b. 1954), Dan (b. 1963), Tom (b. 1970), Sam (b. 1977)\n| occupation = [[Author]], essayist, playwright\n| notable_works = ''[[The Life and Loves of a She-Devil]]'' (1983)\n| relatives = Jane Birkinshaw (1929\u20131969) sister, [[Alan Birkinshaw]] (1944) half-brother\n}}\n\n'''Fay Weldon''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[FRSL]] (born 22 September 1931) is an English author, essayist and playwright.\n\n==Early life==\nWeldon was born '''Franklin Birkinshaw''' in [[Birmingham]], England, in 1931, to a literary family. Her maternal grandfather, [[Edgar Jepson]] (1863\u20131938), her uncle [[Selwyn Jepson]] and her mother [[Margaret Jepson]] wrote novels (the latter sometimes under the nom de plume [[Margaret Jepson|Pearl Bellairs]], from the name of a character in [[Aldous Huxley]]'s short story \"Farcical History of Richard Greenow\").<ref>{{cite book| title=Encyclopedia of the British Short Story| author=Andrew Maunder| date=2013}}</ref> \n\nWeldon grew up in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand, where her father, Frank Thornton Birkinshaw, worked as a doctor. In 1937, when she was six, her parents divorced. She and her sister Jane spent the summers with her father, first in [[Coromandel Peninsula|Coromandel]], later in [[Auckland]]. She attended [[Christchurch Girls' High School]] for two years from 1944.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/our-communities/3043279/Hum-of-lesbianism-at-girls-school|title='Hum of lesbianism' at girls' school|last=Steward|first= Ian|date=9 November 2009|newspaper=Stuff.co.nz|language=English|access-date=15 May 2016}}</ref> Weldon has described herself as a \"plump, cheerful child\", stating in a blog post that began as an unpublished article for the ''[[Daily Mail]]'': \"I was born large, blonde and big-boned into a family of small beautiful women. My mother thought it was unlikely that anyone would marry me, and therefore I would have to pass exams, earn my own living and make my own way in the world. Or that\u2019s what I thought she thought.\" She goes on to explain how this view of herself affected her later writing career. \"I\u2019d be happier to have been be seen as a skinny, feisty child, a slim and serious adult, and a handsome octogenarian with an interesting literary past. But that was not to be, despite a lifetime of diets. It was however a state of affairs which made me write a good few novels with overweight, plain women as their heroines. I\u2019ve always been on their side \u2013 they are the unseen majority.\"<ref name=\"Plain or pretty\">{{Cite web| url=https://fayweldon.co.uk/plain-or-pretty/|first=Fay|last=Weldon|title=Plain or pretty| date=21 June 2016}}</ref> \n\nIn September 1946, when she was 15, she returned to England with her mother and sister. She recalls: \"I was a literary groupie from the antipodes...Not that I had any intention of being a writer at the time \u2013 too much like hard work. All I wanted was to get married and have babies.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/oct/22/fay-weldon-made-in-hampstead-north-london|title=Fay Weldon on Hampstead: \u2018I was a literary groupie from the antipodes\u2019|newspaper=The Guardian|date=22 October 2018}}</ref> She did not see her father again before his death in 1949.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auto da Fay|last=Weldon|first=Fay|publisher=Grove Press|year=2003|isbn=|location=New York|pages=193}}</ref> \n\nIn England Weldon won a scholarship to the all-girls [[South Hampstead High School]], before going on to study [[psychology]] and economics at the [[University of St Andrews]], Scotland. Later she recalled attending classes with the moral philosopher [[Malcolm Knox]], who \"spoke exclusively to the male students, maintaining that women were incapable of moral judgement or objectivity.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auto da Fay|last=Weldon|first=|publisher=|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=218}}</ref> She completed her MA in 1952 and moved to London, where she worked as a clerk at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] for a salary of six pounds a week.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auto da Fay|last=Weldon|first=|publisher=|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=240}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nWeldon had temporary jobs as a waitress and hospital ward orderly before working as a clerk for the Foreign Office where she wrote pamphlets to be dropped in Eastern Europe as part of the Cold War. She had to leave this job after she became pregnant. Later she took a job with [[Crawford's Advertising Agency]], where she worked with the writer [[Elizabeth Smart (Canadian author)|Elizabeth Smart]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auto da |last=Weldon|first=|publisher=|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=316\u201317}}</ref> and where she could earn enough to support herself and her young son (Nicolas). \n\nAs head of [[copywriting]] at [[Ogilvy & Mather|Ogilvy, Benson & Mather]], she was responsible for publicising (but not originating) the phrase \"[[Go to work on an egg]]\". She coined the slogan \"Vodka gets you drunker quicker,\" saying in a ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' interview:<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/religion/Story/0,,1865034,00.html | work=The Guardian | first=Stuart | last=Jeffries | title=Fay Weldon who has found God after 70 years as atheist talks to Stuart Jeffries | date=12 September 2006}}</ref> \"It just seemed ... to be obvious that people who wanted to get drunk fast needed to know this.\" Her bosses disagreed and suppressed it.\n\n==Literary career==\n===Writing career===\n[[File:Gerard_Casey_and_Fay_Weldon_appearing_on_After_Dark_in_1997.jpg|thumb|left|Appearing with [[Gerard Casey (philosopher)|Gerard Casey]] on British television discussion programme ''[[After Dark (TV series)|After Dark]]'' in 1997]]\nIn 1963 Weldon began writing for radio and television. In 1967, her first novel, ''The Fat Woman's Joke'' was published. \"When I submitted my first novel in 1966 it was accepted without demur. I thought this was because I was a wonderful writer, But it wasn't. It was because I had learned to have nothing turned down.\"<ref>{{Cite book| title=Why Will No-one Publish My Novel?| last=Weldon| first=|page=182}}</ref> She subsequently built a very successful and prolific career, publishing over thirty novels, collections of short stories, films for television, newspaper and magazine articles and becoming a well-known face and voice on the [[BBC]]. She has described herself as a \"writeaholic\"<ref>{{Cite book| title=Why Will No-one Publish My Novel?| last=Weldon| first=|page=179}}</ref> .\n\nIn 1971 Weldon wrote the first episode of the landmark television series ''[[Upstairs, Downstairs (1971 TV series)|Upstairs, Downstairs]]'', [170] for which she won a [[Writers Guild of America|Writers Guild]] award for Best British TV Series Script. In 1980 Weldon wrote the screenplay for director/producer [[John Goldschmidt]]'s television movie ''Life for Christine'', which told the true story of a 15-year-old girl's life imprisonment. The film was shown in prime-time on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] Network by [[Granada Television]]. She also wrote the screenplay for the 1980 BBC [[Pride and Prejudice (1980 TV series)|miniseries adaptation]] of [[Jane Austen]]'s ''[[Pride and Prejudice]]'', starring [[Elizabeth Garvie]] and [[David Rintoul]]. In 1989, she contributed to the book for the [[Petula Clark]] West End musical ''[[Someone Like You (musical)|Someone Like You]]''.\n\nWeldon's most celebrated work is her 1983 novel ''[[The Life and Loves of a She-Devil]]'', which she wrote at the age of 52. \n\nHer novel ''The Hearts and Lives of Men'' was written and published in serial form, appearing in the British magazine ''[[Woman (UK magazine)|Woman]]'' between 1 February and 15 November 1986. She told ''[[The New York Times]]'', \"It was written as the Dickens novels were written....You made it up as you went along, confined by the structure of the story, which is going to go on for you don't know how long\u2014but you have to be able to bring it to an end with three weeks' warning.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/10/25/specials/weldon-men.html|title=Little Nell, Or Virtue Rewarded|last=Wilcox|first=James|date=March 13, 1988|website=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Other literary activities===\nIn 1996, she was a member of the jury at the [[46th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale 1996\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1996/04_jury_1996/04_Jury_1996.html |title=Berlinale: 1996 Juries |accessdate=1 January 2012 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref> She was also chair of judges for the 1983 [[Booker Prize]]. The judging for that prize produced a draw between [[J. M. Coetzee]]'s ''[[Life & Times of Michael K]]'' and [[Salman Rushdie]]'s ''[[Shame (Rushdie novel)|Shame]]'', leaving Weldon to choose between the two. According to Stephen Moss in ''[[The Guardian]]'', \"Her arm was bent and she chose Rushdie\" only to change her mind as the result was being phoned through.<ref>{{cite news|first=Stephen|last=Moss|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/sep/18/bookerprize2001.thebookerprize|title=Is the Booker fixed?|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|date=18 September 2001|accessdate=18 September 2001}}</ref>\n\nWeldon was appointed Professor of Creative Writing at [[Brunel University]] in West London in 2006: \"A great writer needs a certain personality and a natural talent for language, but there is a great deal that can be taught \u2013 how to put words together quickly and efficiently to make a point, how to be graceful and eloquent, how to convey emotion, how to build up tension, and how to create alternative worlds.\" In 2012 Weldon she was appointed Professor of Creative Writing at [[Bath Spa University]], where she shares an office with Professor [[Maggie Gee (novelist)|Maggie Gee]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Weldon and Hensher head to Bath Spa|first=Katie|last=Allen|url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/weldon-and-hensher-head-bath-spa.html|work=[[The Bookseller]]|date=28 September 2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nWeldon serves together with [[Daniel Pipes]] as the most notable foreign members of the board of the [[International Free Press Society|Danish Press Freedom Society (Trykkefrihedsselskabet)]].\n\n===Awards===\n\n* [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain|Writers' Guild]] Award for the pilot of the original TV programme ''Upstairs Downstairs'' (1973)\n* The [[Man Booker Prize]] Best Novel nominee (1979) for ''Praxis''\n* [[Society of Authors]] Travelling Scholarship (1980)\n* Winner of the [[Los Angeles Times Book Prize| ''Los Angeles Times'' Fiction Prize]] for ''The Heart of the Country'' (1989)\n* [[Whitbread Prize]] Best Novel nominee (1996) for ''Worst Fears''\n* PEN/Macmillan Silver Pen Award (1996) for ''[[Wicked Women]]''\n* [[Order of the British Empire| Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (CBE)]] 2001\n\n===Feminism===\nA self-declared feminist, Weldon's work features what she has described as \"overweight, plain women\" \u2013 as she has deliberately sought, she has said, to write about and give a voice to women who are often overlooked or not featured in the media. She says there were many reasons why she became a feminist, including \"appalling\" lack of equal opportunities and the myth that women were supported by male relatives. \"What drove me to feminism fifty years ago was the myth that men were the breadwinners and women kept house and looked pretty.\"<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://fayweldon.co.uk/myths-of-modern-women-1/|first=Fay|last=Weldon|title=Myths of modern women: 1| date=29 August 2013}}</ref> She notes that the turning point for her, however, was the outright sexism in the media industry at that time, such as when she attended a casting session of a TV drama she had written and watched the male director and producer \"...cast the lead by flicking through Spotlight and just choosing the girl they both most fancied. And they were amazed when I objected: female skill, talent, experience, intelligence meant nothing to them\".<ref name=\"Plain or pretty\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1953, while working at the Foreign Office, Weldon became pregnant by a musician she met who was moonlighting as a doorman. She has said that while she wanted the child (son Nicolas), she decided she didn't want the father. In 1957, tired of struggling to support herself as a single mother, she married Ronald Bateman, a headmaster 25 years her senior.<ref name=\"Saner\">Saner, Emine, [https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2009/aug/22/fay-weldon-interview-saturday \"'I'm the only feminist there is \u2013 the others are all out of step'\"], ''The Guardian'', 22 August 2009.</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Auto da Fay|last=Weldon|first=Fay|publisher=Grove Press|year=2003|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> They lived together in [[Acton, London]], for two years, until the marriage ended.<ref name=\"Saner\"/>\n\nIn 1961, at 29 Weldon met her second husband, Ron Weldon, a jazz musician and antiques dealer.<ref name =\"Grice\">Grice, Elizabeth, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4980926/Fay-Weldon-Dying-I-dont-want-to-do-that-again.html \"Fay Weldon: 'Dying? I don't want to do that again'\"], ''Daily Telegraph'', 12 March 2009.</ref> They married in 1963 when Fay was heavily pregnant with her second son Dan (born 1963). They lived in [[East Compton, Somerset|East Compton]], Somerset, later having two more sons, Tom (1970) and Sam (1977). It was while she was pregnant with Dan that Weldon began writing for radio and television. \nDuring her marriage to Ron Weldon, the couple visited therapists regularly. In 1992 Ron left Fay for his astrological therapist, who had told him that the couple's astrological signs were incompatible.<ref name=\"Saner\"/> They began divorce proceedings, although Ron died in 1994, just eight hours before the divorce was finalised. <ref name=\"wellsjournal-20130124\">{{cite news |url=http://www.wellsjournal.co.uk/Somerset-boast-host-literary-connections/story-17950509-detail/story.html |title=Somerset can boast a whole host of literary connections |newspaper=Wells Journal |date=24 January 2013 |accessdate=15 February 2016 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994 Weldon married Nick Fox, a poet who is also her manager, with whom she currently lives in [[Dorset]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3576743/The-life-and-loves-of-Fay-Weldon.html|first=Nigel |last=Farndale|title=The Life And Loves of Fay Weldon|website=The Telegraph|year=2 May 2002}}</ref> \n\nIn 2000 Weldon became a member of the [[Church of England]] and was confirmed in [[St Paul's Cathedral]]. She states that she likes to think that she was \"converted by [[Saint Paul (apostle)|St Paul]]\".<ref>Weldon, Fay, \"Converted by St Paul\", in Caroline Chartres (ed.), ''Why I Am Still an Anglican'', Continuum, 2006, p. 134.</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn a 1998 interview for the ''[[Radio Times]]'' Weldon claimed that rape \"isn't the worst thing that can happen to a woman if you're safe, alive and unmarked after the event.\"<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/122813.stm \"Fay Weldon: Rape isn't the worst thing that can happen \"], BBC News, 30 June 1998.</ref> She was roundly condemned by feminists for this assertion.<ref name=\"independent-condemned\">{{cite news |last1=Blamires|first1=Diana |title=Fay Weldon causes rape storm |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/fay-weldon-causes-rape-storm-1168537.html |accessdate=13 April 2017 |work=The Independent |date=30 June 1998}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001 Weldon's novel ''[[The Bulgari Connection]]'' became notorious for its product placement, naming the jewellers not only in the title but another 33 times, while a minimum of 12 times was stipulated in the \u00a318,000 contract.\n\nWeldon has defended the so-called \"[[Snowflake Generation]]\", saying: \"We should stop being beastly to the snowflakes.... Today\u2019s young grow up into a violent, angry, unstable environment, all too likely to end up jobless, homeless and childless, unlikely to reach their full potential. They are probably the most despairing generation ever conceived. The least we can do is not add to their burden by slagging them off.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/sep/28/blame-parents-for-snowflake-millennials-says-author-fay-weldon|title=Blame parents for \u2018snowflake\u2019 millennials|last=Alberge|first=Dalya|website=The Guardian|date=28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Literary works==\n===Novels===\n*''[[The Fat Woman's Joke]]'' (1967)\n*''[[Down Among the Women]]'' (1971)\n*''[[Little Sisters (Fay Weldon)|Little Sisters]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Female Friends]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Remember Me (Fay Weldon)|Remember Me]]'' (1976)\n*''[[Praxis (novel)|Praxis]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Puffball (novel)|Puffball]]'' (1980)\n*''[[The President's Child]]'' (1982)\n*''[[The Shrapnel Academy]]'' (1986)\n*''[[The Heart of the Country]]'' (1987)\n*''[[The Hearts and Lives of Men]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Leader of the Band (novel)|Leader of the Band]]'' (1988)\n*''[[The Cloning of Joanna May]]'' (1989)\n*''[[Darcy's Utopia]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Growing Rich]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Life Force (Fay Weldon)|Life Force]]'' (1992)\n*''Question of Timing'' (1992)\n*''[[Affliction (1994 novel)|Affliction]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Splitting (novel)|Splitting]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Worst Fears]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Big Women]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Rhode Island Blues]]'' (2000)\n*''[[The Bulgari Connection]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Mantrapped]]'' (2004)\n*''[[She May Not Leave]]'' (2006)\n*''[[The Spa Decameron]]'' (2007)\n*''[[The Stepmother's Diary]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Chalcot Crescent]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Kehua!]]'' (2010)\n\n===Series===\n'''She Devil'''\n*''[[The Life and Loves of a She-Devil]]'' (1983)\n*''Death of a She Devil'' (2017)\n\n'''Love and Inheritance'''\n*''[[Habits of the House]]'' (2012)\n*''Long Live the King'' (2013)\n*''The New Countess'' (2013)\n*''Love and Inheritance Trilogy'' (2013) \u2013 Omnibus\n\n'''Spoils of War'''\n*''Before the War'' (2017)\n*''After the Peace'' (2018)\n\n'''The Chapbooks'''\n*''[[The Rules of Life]]'' (1987)\n*''Wolf the Mechanical Dog'' (1988)\n*''The Roots of Violence'' (1989)\n*''Party Puddle'' (1989)\n\n===Non-fiction===\n* ''[[Letters to Alice: On First Reading Jane Austen]]'' (1984)\n* ''Rebecca West'' (1985)\n* ''Sacred Cows'' (1989)\n* ''[[Godless in Eden]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Auto da Fay]]'' (2002) \u2013 an autobiography of her early years. The title is an [[allusion]] to ''[[auto da fe]]''\n* ''[[What Makes Women Happy]]'' (2006)\n* ''Why Will No-One Publish My Novel?'' (2018)\n\n===Plays===\n* ''Action Replay - A Play'' (1980), first performed 1979 (Birmingham Repertory Studio Theatre); <ref>Published by A Samuel French, Acting Edition.</ref>\n\n===Anthologies containing stories by Fay Weldon===\n* ''The 4th Bumper Book of Ghost Stories'' (1980)\n* ''The Literary Ghost'' (1991)\n* ''The Penguin Book of Modern Fantasy by Women'' (1995)\n* ''The Oxford Book of Twentieth-Century Ghost Stories'' (1996)\n* ''Mistresses of the Dark'' (1998)\n* ''The Mammoth Book of Twentieth-Century Ghost Stories'' (1998)\n* ''Crossing the Border'' (1998)\n* ''The Mammoth Book of Haunted House Stories'' (2000)\n\n===Collections and Omnibus===\n* ''Watching Me, Watching You'' (1981)\n* ''Polaris'' (1985)\n* ''Moon Over Minneapolis'' (1991)\n* ''Angel, All Innocence'' (1995)\n* ''[[Wicked Women]]'' (1995)\n* ''A Hard Time to Be a Father'' (1998)\n* ''Nothing to Wear and Nowhere to Hide'' (2002)\n* ''Poolside'' (2007) - with [[Alice Adams (writer)|Alice Adams]], [[Amy Bloom]], [[John Cheever]], [[Ernest Hemingway]], [[A. M. Homes]], [[Andrea Lee (suthor)|Andrea Lee]], [[Joyce Carol Oates]], [[Edna O'Brien]], [[Julie Orringer]], [[James Purdy]], [[Graham Swift]], [[John Updike]] and [[David Foster Wallace]]\n* ''Great Escapes'' (2008) - with [[Amanda Craig]], [[Virginia Ironside]], [[Kathy Lette]], [[Deborah Moggach]], [[Kate Mosse]], [[Lesley Pearse]], [[Rose Tremain]], [[Jane Elizabeth Varley]] and [[Isabel Wolff]]\n* ''Fay Weldon Omnibus: Collected Works of Fay Weldon'' (2014)\n* ''Mischief'' (2015)\n* ''The Collected Novels Volume One'' (2018)\n* ''The Collected Novels Volume Two'' (2018)\n* ''The Collected Novels Volume Three'' (2018)\n\n===Short stories and novellas===\n* \"Angel, All Innocence\" (1977) \u2013 short story\n* \"[[Weekend (Fay Weldon)|Weekend]]\" (1978) \u2013 short story\n* \"Spirit of the House\" (1980) \u2013 short story\n* \"Watching Me, Watching You\" (1981) \u2013 short story\n* \"Down the Clinical Disco\" (1985) \u2013 short story\n* \"A Good Sound Marriage\" (''US Journal'', 1991) \u2013 short story\n* ''The Ted Dreams'' (2014) \u2013 novella\n\n==Criticism and reviews==\n\n====''Chalcot Crescent''====\n*{{cite journal |last=Guinness |first=Molly |date=12 September 2009 |title=Family album |journal=[[The Spectator]] |volume=311 |issue=9446 |pages=37\u201338 |url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/books/5316806/family-album.thtml |accessdate=16 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718224032/http://www.spectator.co.uk/books/5316806/family-album.thtml |archivedate=18 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n*{{cite journal|date=5 April 2012|title=REVIEW : Fay Weldon \u2013 Chalcot Crescent|journal=Upcoming4.me|url=http://upcoming4.me/news/book-news/review-fay-weldon-chalcot-crescent|accessdate=30 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630171418/http://upcoming4.me/news/book-news/review-fay-weldon-chalcot-crescent|archivedate=30 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{official website}} \n* Rosemary Goring, [http://www.heraldscotland.com/books-poetry/interviews/fay-weldon-on-her-30th-novel.18165685 \"Fay Weldon on her 30th novel\"] (interview), ''Herald Scotland'', 20 July 2012.\n* Hester Lacey, [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/ea3c5c02-b622-11e1-a14a-00144feabdc0.html#axzz21wP6qj8g \"The Inventory: Fay Weldon\",] ''Financial Times'', 27 July 2012.\n* Stuart Jeffries, [https://www.theguardian.com/religion/Story/0,,1865034,00.html \"Lie back and think of Jesus\"], ''The Guardian'', 5 September 2006. Interview and review of ''What Makes Women Happy''. Weldon describes her near-death experience and spiritual journey from atheism to belief in God.\n* Fay Weldon, [https://archive.is/20130505071030/http://www.saga.co.uk/saga-magazine/4-fay-weldon.aspx \"My left knee\"], ''[[Saga Magazine]]'', 10 October 2011. Weldon writes candidly about having her knee replaced at 80, and her fears prior to the operation.\n* {{LCAuth|n50002441|Fay Weldon|92|ue}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weldon, Fay}}\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:Feminist writers]]\n[[Category:English screenwriters]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of Bath Spa University]]\n[[Category:Academics of Brunel University London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Copywriters]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:People from Hampstead]]\n[[Category:People from Alvechurch]]\n[[Category:People educated at South Hampstead High School]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English author, essayist and playwright}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[FRSL]] \n| name = Fay Weldon\n| image = Fay-Weldon Copenhagen-2008.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Weldon at the 2008 Copenhagen Book Fair\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1931|9|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist |\n* {{marriage|Ronald Bateman|1957|1959|end=div}}\n* {{marriage|Ron Weldon|1963|1994|end=d.}}\n* {{marriage|Nick Fox|1994}}\n}}\n| children           = Nicolas (b. 1954), Dan (b. 1963), Tom (b. 1970), Sam (b. 1977)\n| occupation = [[Author]], essayist, playwright\n| notable_works = ''[[The Life and Loves of a She-Devil]]'' (1983)\n| relatives = Jane Birkinshaw (1929\u20131969) sister, [[Alan Birkinshaw]] (1944) half-brother\n}}\n\n'''Fay Weldon''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[FRSL]] (born 22 September 1931) is an English author, essayist and playwright.\n\n==Early life==\nWeldon was born '''Franklin Birkinshaw''' in [[Birmingham]], England, in 1931, to a literary family. Her maternal grandfather, [[Edgar Jepson]] (1863\u20131938), her uncle [[Selwyn Jepson]] and her mother [[Margaret Jepson]] wrote novels (the latter sometimes under the nom de plume [[Margaret Jepson|Pearl Bellairs]], from the name of a character in [[Aldous Huxley]]'s short story \"Farcical History of Richard Greenow\").<ref>{{cite book| title=Encyclopedia of the British Short Story| author=Andrew Maunder| date=2013}}</ref> \n\nWeldon grew up in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand, where her father, Frank Thornton Birkinshaw, worked as a doctor. In 1937, when she was six, her parents divorced. She and her sister Jane spent the summers with her father, first in [[Coromandel Peninsula|Coromandel]], later in [[Auckland]]. She attended [[Christchurch Girls' High School]] for two years from 1944.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/our-communities/3043279/Hum-of-lesbianism-at-girls-school|title='Hum of lesbianism' at girls' school|last=Steward|first= Ian|date=9 November 2009|newspaper=Stuff.co.nz|language=English|access-date=15 May 2016}}</ref> Weldon has described herself as a \"plump, cheerful child\", stating in a blog post that began as an unpublished article for the ''[[Daily Mail]]'': \"I was born large, blonde and big-boned into a family of small beautiful women. My mother thought it was unlikely that anyone would marry me, and therefore I would have to pass exams, earn my own living and make my own way in the world. Or that\u2019s what I thought she thought.\" She goes on to explain how this view of herself affected her later writing career. \"I\u2019d be happier to have been be seen as a skinny, feisty child, a slim and serious adult, and a handsome octogenarian with an interesting literary past. But that was not to be, despite a lifetime of diets. It was however a state of affairs which made me write a good few novels with overweight, plain women as their heroines. I\u2019ve always been on their side \u2013 they are the unseen majority.\"<ref name=\"Plain or pretty\">{{Cite web| url=https://fayweldon.co.uk/plain-or-pretty/|first=Fay|last=Weldon|title=Plain or pretty| date=21 June 2016}}</ref> \n\nIn September 1946, when she was 15, she returned to England with her mother and sister. She recalls: \"I was a literary groupie from the antipodes...Not that I had any intention of being a writer at the time \u2013 too much like hard work. All I wanted was to get married and have babies.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/oct/22/fay-weldon-made-in-hampstead-north-london|title=Fay Weldon on Hampstead: \u2018I was a literary groupie from the antipodes\u2019|newspaper=The Guardian|date=22 October 2018}}</ref> She did not see her father again before his death in 1949.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auto da Fay|last=Weldon|first=Fay|publisher=Grove Press|year=2003|isbn=|location=New York|pages=193}}</ref> \n\nIn England Weldon won a scholarship to the all-girls [[South Hampstead High School]], before going on to study [[psychology]] and economics at the [[University of St Andrews]], Scotland. Later she recalled attending classes with the moral philosopher [[Malcolm Knox]], who \"spoke exclusively to the male students, maintaining that women were incapable of moral judgement or objectivity.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auto da Fay|last=Weldon|first=|publisher=|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=218}}</ref> She completed her MA in 1952 and moved to London, where she worked as a clerk at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] for a salary of six pounds a week.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auto da Fay|last=Weldon|first=|publisher=|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=240}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nWeldon had temporary jobs as a waitress and hospital ward orderly before working as a clerk for the Foreign Office where she wrote pamphlets to be dropped in Eastern Europe as part of the Cold War. She had to leave this job after she became pregnant. Later she took a job with [[Crawford's Advertising Agency]], where she worked with the writer [[Elizabeth Smart (Canadian author)|Elizabeth Smart]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auto da |last=Weldon|first=|publisher=|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=316\u201317}}</ref> and where she could earn enough to support herself and her young son (Nicolas). \n\nAs head of [[copywriting]] at [[Ogilvy & Mather|Ogilvy, Benson & Mather]], she was responsible for publicising (but not originating) the phrase \"[[Go to work on an egg]]\". She coined the slogan \"Vodka gets you drunker quicker,\" saying in a ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' interview:<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/religion/Story/0,,1865034,00.html | work=The Guardian | first=Stuart | last=Jeffries | title=Fay Weldon who has found God after 70 years as atheist talks to Stuart Jeffries | date=12 September 2006}}</ref> \"It just seemed ... to be obvious that people who wanted to get drunk fast needed to know this.\" Her bosses disagreed and suppressed it.\n\n==Literary career==\n===Writing career===\n[[File:Gerard_Casey_and_Fay_Weldon_appearing_on_After_Dark_in_1997.jpg|thumb|left|Appearing with [[Gerard Casey (philosopher)|Gerard Casey]] on British television discussion programme ''[[After Dark (TV series)|After Dark]]'' in 1997]]\nIn 1963 Weldon began writing for radio and television. In 1967, her first novel, ''The Fat Woman's Joke'' was published. \"When I submitted my first novel in 1966 it was accepted without demur. I thought this was because I was a wonderful writer, But it wasn't. It was because I had learned to have nothing turned down.\"<ref>{{Cite book| title=Why Will No-one Publish My Novel?| last=Weldon| first=|page=182}}</ref> She subsequently built a very successful and prolific career, publishing over thirty novels, collections of short stories, films for television, newspaper and magazine articles and becoming a well-known face and voice on the [[BBC]]. She has described herself as a \"writeaholic\"<ref>{{Cite book| title=Why Will No-one Publish My Novel?| last=Weldon| first=|page=179}}</ref> .\n\nIn 1971 Weldon wrote the first episode of the landmark television series ''[[Upstairs, Downstairs (1971 TV series)|Upstairs, Downstairs]]'', [170] for which she won a [[Writers Guild of America|Writers Guild]] award for Best British TV Series Script. In 1980 Weldon wrote the screenplay for director/producer [[John Goldschmidt]]'s television movie ''Life for Christine'', which told the true story of a 15-year-old girl's life imprisonment. The film was shown in prime-time on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] Network by [[Granada Television]]. She also wrote the screenplay for the 1980 BBC [[Pride and Prejudice (1980 TV series)|miniseries adaptation]] of [[Jane Austen]]'s ''[[Pride and Prejudice]]'', starring [[Elizabeth Garvie]] and [[David Rintoul]]. In 1989, she contributed to the book for the [[Petula Clark]] West End musical ''[[Someone Like You (musical)|Someone Like You]]''.\n\nWeldon's most celebrated work is her 1983 novel ''[[The Life and Loves of a She-Devil]]'', which she wrote at the age of 52. \n\nHer novel ''The Hearts and Lives of Men'' was written and published in serial form, appearing in the British magazine ''[[Woman (UK magazine)|Woman]]'' between 1 February and 15 November 1986. She told ''[[The New York Times]]'', \"It was written as the Dickens novels were written....You made it up as you went along, confined by the structure of the story, which is going to go on for you don't know how long\u2014but you have to be able to bring it to an end with three weeks' warning.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/10/25/specials/weldon-men.html|title=Little Nell, Or Virtue Rewarded|last=Wilcox|first=James|date=March 13, 1988|website=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Other literary activities===\nIn 1996, she was a member of the jury at the [[46th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale 1996\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1996/04_jury_1996/04_Jury_1996.html |title=Berlinale: 1996 Juries |accessdate=1 January 2012 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref> She was also chair of judges for the 1983 [[Booker Prize]]. The judging for that prize produced a draw between [[J. M. Coetzee]]'s ''[[Life & Times of Michael K]]'' and [[Salman Rushdie]]'s ''[[Shame (Rushdie novel)|Shame]]'', leaving Weldon to choose between the two. According to Stephen Moss in ''[[The Guardian]]'', \"Her arm was bent and she chose Rushdie\" only to change her mind as the result was being phoned through.<ref>{{cite news|first=Stephen|last=Moss|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/sep/18/bookerprize2001.thebookerprize|title=Is the Booker fixed?|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|date=18 September 2001|accessdate=18 September 2001}}</ref>\n\nWeldon was appointed Professor of Creative Writing at [[Brunel University]] in West London in 2006: \"A great writer needs a certain personality and a natural talent for language, but there is a great deal that can be taught \u2013 how to put words together quickly and efficiently to make a point, how to be graceful and eloquent, how to convey emotion, how to build up tension, and how to create alternative worlds.\" In 2012 Weldon she was appointed Professor of Creative Writing at [[Bath Spa University]], where she shares an office with Professor [[Maggie Gee (novelist)|Maggie Gee]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Weldon and Hensher head to Bath Spa|first=Katie|last=Allen|url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/weldon-and-hensher-head-bath-spa.html|work=[[The Bookseller]]|date=28 September 2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nWeldon serves together with [[Daniel Pipes]] as the most notable foreign members of the board of the [[International Free Press Society|Danish Press Freedom Society (Trykkefrihedsselskabet)]].\n\n===Awards===\n\n* [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain|Writers' Guild]] Award for the pilot of the original TV programme ''Upstairs Downstairs'' (1973)\n* The [[Man Booker Prize]] Best Novel nominee (1979) for ''Praxis''\n* [[Society of Authors]] Travelling Scholarship (1980)\n* Winner of the [[Los Angeles Times Book Prize| ''Los Angeles Times'' Fiction Prize]] for ''The Heart of the Country'' (1989)\n* [[Whitbread Prize]] Best Novel nominee (1996) for ''Worst Fears''\n* PEN/Macmillan Silver Pen Award (1996) for ''[[Wicked Women]]''\n* [[Order of the British Empire| Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (CBE)]] 2001\n\n===Feminism===\nA self-declared feminist, Weldon's work features what she has described as \"overweight, plain women\" \u2013 as she has deliberately sought, she has said, to write about and give a voice to women that are often overlooked or not featured in the media. She says there were many reasons why she became a feminist, including \"appalling\" lack of equal opportunities and the myth that women were supported by male relatives. \"What drove me to feminism fifty years ago was the myth that men were the breadwinners and women kept house and looked pretty.\"<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://fayweldon.co.uk/myths-of-modern-women-1/|first=Fay|last=Weldon|title=Myths of modern women: 1| date=29 August 2013}}</ref> She notes that the turning point for her, however, was the outright sexism in the media industry at that time, such as when she attended a casting session of a TV drama she had written and watched the male director and producer \"...cast the lead by flicking through Spotlight and just choosing the girl they both most fancied. And they were amazed when I objected: female skill, talent, experience, intelligence meant nothing to them\".<ref name=\"Plain or pretty\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1953, while working at the Foreign Office, Weldon became pregnant by a musician she met who was moonlighting as a doorman. She has said that while she wanted the child (son Nicolas), she decided she didn't want the father. In 1957, tired of struggling to support herself as a single mother, she married Ronald Bateman, a headmaster 25 years her senior.<ref name=\"Saner\">Saner, Emine, [https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2009/aug/22/fay-weldon-interview-saturday \"'I'm the only feminist there is \u2013 the others are all out of step'\"], ''The Guardian'', 22 August 2009.</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Auto da Fay|last=Weldon|first=Fay|publisher=Grove Press|year=2003|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> They lived together in [[Acton, London]], for two years, until the marriage ended.<ref name=\"Saner\"/>\n\nIn 1961, at 29 Weldon met her second husband Ron Weldon, a jazz musician and antiques dealer.<ref name =\"Grice\">Grice, Elizabeth, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4980926/Fay-Weldon-Dying-I-dont-want-to-do-that-again.html \"Fay Weldon: 'Dying? I don't want to do that again'\"], ''Daily Telegraph'', 12 March 2009.</ref> They married in 1963 when Fay was heavily pregnant with her second son Dan (born 1963). They lived in [[East Compton, Somerset|East Compton]], Somerset, later having two more sons, Tom (1970) and Sam (1977). It was while she was pregnant with Dan that Weldon began writing for radio and television. \nDuring her marriage to Ron Weldon, the couple visited therapists regularly. In 1992 Ron left Fay for his astrological therapist, who had told him that the couple's astrological signs were incompatible.<ref name=\"Saner\"/> They began divorce proceedings, although Ron died in 1994 eight hours before the divorce was finalised. <ref name=\"wellsjournal-20130124\">{{cite news |url=http://www.wellsjournal.co.uk/Somerset-boast-host-literary-connections/story-17950509-detail/story.html |title=Somerset can boast a whole host of literary connections |newspaper=Wells Journal |date=24 January 2013 |accessdate=15 February 2016 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994 Weldon married Nick Fox, a poet who is also her manager, with whom she currently lives in [[Dorset]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3576743/The-life-and-loves-of-Fay-Weldon.html|first=Nigel |last=Farndale|title=The Life And Loves of Fay Weldon|website=The Telegraph|year=2 May 2002}}</ref> \n\nIn 2000 Weldon became a member of the [[Church of England]] and was confirmed in [[St Paul's Cathedral]]. She states that she likes to think that she was \"converted by [[Saint Paul (apostle)|St Paul]]\".<ref>Weldon, Fay, \"Converted by St Paul\", in Caroline Chartres (ed.), ''Why I Am Still an Anglican'', Continuum, 2006, p. 134.</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn a 1998 interview for the ''[[Radio Times]]'' Weldon claimed that rape \"isn't the worst thing that can happen to a woman if you're safe, alive and unmarked after the event.\"<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/122813.stm \"Fay Weldon: Rape isn't the worst thing that can happen \"], BBC News, 30 June 1998.</ref> She was roundly condemned by feminists for this assertion.<ref name=\"independent-condemned\">{{cite news |last1=Blamires|first1=Diana |title=Fay Weldon causes rape storm |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/fay-weldon-causes-rape-storm-1168537.html |accessdate=13 April 2017 |work=The Independent |date=30 June 1998}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001 Weldon's novel ''[[The Bulgari Connection]]'' became notorious for its product placement, naming the jewellers not only in the title but another 33 times, while 12 times at least was appointed in the \u00a318,000 contract.\n\nWeldon has defended the so-called \"[[Snowflake Generation]]\", saying: \"We should stop being beastly to the snowflakes.... Today\u2019s young grow up into a violent, angry, unstable environment, all too likely to end up jobless, homeless and childless, unlikely to reach their full potential. They are probably the most despairing generation ever conceived. The least we can do is not add to their burden by slagging them off.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/sep/28/blame-parents-for-snowflake-millennials-says-author-fay-weldon|title=Blame parents for \u2018snowflake\u2019 millennials|last=Alberge|first=Dalya|website=The Guardian|date=28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Literary works==\n===Novels===\n*''[[The Fat Woman's Joke]]'' (1967)\n*''[[Down Among the Women]]'' (1971)\n*''[[Little Sisters (Fay Weldon)|Little Sisters]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Female Friends]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Remember Me (Fay Weldon)|Remember Me]]'' (1976)\n*''[[Praxis (novel)|Praxis]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Puffball (novel)|Puffball]]'' (1980)\n*''[[The President's Child]]'' (1982)\n*''[[The Shrapnel Academy]]'' (1986)\n*''[[The Heart of the Country]]'' (1987)\n*''[[The Hearts and Lives of Men]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Leader of the Band (novel)|Leader of the Band]]'' (1988)\n*''[[The Cloning of Joanna May]]'' (1989)\n*''[[Darcy's Utopia]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Growing Rich]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Life Force (Fay Weldon)|Life Force]]'' (1992)\n*''Question of Timing'' (1992)\n*''[[Affliction (1994 novel)|Affliction]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Splitting (novel)|Splitting]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Worst Fears]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Big Women]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Rhode Island Blues]]'' (2000)\n*''[[The Bulgari Connection]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Mantrapped]]'' (2004)\n*''[[She May Not Leave]]'' (2006)\n*''[[The Spa Decameron]]'' (2007)\n*''[[The Stepmother's Diary]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Chalcot Crescent]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Kehua!]]'' (2010)\n\n===Series===\n'''She Devil'''\n*''[[The Life and Loves of a She-Devil]]'' (1983)\n*''Death of a She Devil'' (2017)\n\n'''Love and Inheritance'''\n*''[[Habits of the House]]'' (2012)\n*''Long Live the King'' (2013)\n*''The New Countess'' (2013)\n*''Love and Inheritance Trilogy'' (2013) \u2013 Omnibus\n\n'''Spoils of War'''\n*''Before the War'' (2017)\n*''After the Peace'' (2018)\n\n'''The Chapbooks'''\n*''[[The Rules of Life]]'' (1987)\n*''Wolf the Mechanical Dog'' (1988)\n*''The Roots of Violence'' (1989)\n*''Party Puddle'' (1989)\n\n===Non-fiction===\n* ''[[Letters to Alice: On First Reading Jane Austen]]'' (1984)\n* ''Rebecca West'' (1985)\n* ''Sacred Cows'' (1989)\n* ''[[Godless in Eden]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Auto da Fay]]'' (2002) \u2013 an autobiography of her early years. The title is an [[allusion]] to ''[[auto da fe]]''\n* ''[[What Makes Women Happy]]'' (2006)\n* ''Why Will No-One Publish My Novel?'' (2018)\n\n===Plays===\n* ''Action Replay - A Play'' (1980), first performed 1979 (Birmingham Repertory Studio Theatre); <ref>Published by A Samuel French, Acting Edition.</ref>\n\n===Anthologies containing stories by Fay Weldon===\n* ''The 4th Bumper Book of Ghost Stories'' (1980)\n* ''The Literary Ghost'' (1991)\n* ''The Penguin Book of Modern Fantasy by Women'' (1995)\n* ''The Oxford Book of Twentieth-Century Ghost Stories'' (1996)\n* ''Mistresses of the Dark'' (1998)\n* ''The Mammoth Book of Twentieth-Century Ghost Stories'' (1998)\n* ''Crossing the Border'' (1998)\n* ''The Mammoth Book of Haunted House Stories'' (2000)\n\n===Collections and Omnibus===\n* ''Watching Me, Watching You'' (1981)\n* ''Polaris'' (1985)\n* ''Moon Over Minneapolis'' (1991)\n* ''Angel, All Innocence'' (1995)\n* ''[[Wicked Women]]'' (1995)\n* ''A Hard Time to Be a Father'' (1998)\n* ''Nothing to Wear and Nowhere to Hide'' (2002)\n* ''Poolside'' (2007) - with [[Alice Adams (writer)|Alice Adams]], [[Amy Bloom]], [[John Cheever]], [[Ernest Hemingway]], [[A. M. Homes]], [[Andrea Lee (suthor)|Andrea Lee]], [[Joyce Carol Oates]], [[Edna O'Brien]], [[Julie Orringer]], [[James Purdy]], [[Graham Swift]], [[John Updike]] and [[David Foster Wallace]]\n* ''Great Escapes'' (2008) - with [[Amanda Craig]], [[Virginia Ironside]], [[Kathy Lette]], [[Deborah Moggach]], [[Kate Mosse]], [[Lesley Pearse]], [[Rose Tremain]], [[Jane Elizabeth Varley]] and [[Isabel Wolff]]\n* ''Fay Weldon Omnibus: Collected Works of Fay Weldon'' (2014)\n* ''Mischief'' (2015)\n* ''The Collected Novels Volume One'' (2018)\n* ''The Collected Novels Volume Two'' (2018)\n* ''The Collected Novels Volume Three'' (2018)\n\n===Short stories and novellas===\n* \"Angel, All Innocence\" (1977) \u2013 short story\n* \"[[Weekend (Fay Weldon)|Weekend]]\" (1978) \u2013 short story\n* \"Spirit of the House\" (1980) \u2013 short story\n* \"Watching Me, Watching You\" (1981) \u2013 short story\n* \"Down the Clinical Disco\" (1985) \u2013 short story\n* \"A Good Sound Marriage\" (''US Journal'', 1991) \u2013 short story\n* ''The Ted Dreams'' (2014) \u2013 novella\n\n==Criticism and reviews==\n\n====''Chalcot Crescent''====\n*{{cite journal |last=Guinness |first=Molly |date=12 September 2009 |title=Family album |journal=[[The Spectator]] |volume=311 |issue=9446 |pages=37\u201338 |url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/books/5316806/family-album.thtml |accessdate=16 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718224032/http://www.spectator.co.uk/books/5316806/family-album.thtml |archivedate=18 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n*{{cite journal|date=5 April 2012|title=REVIEW : Fay Weldon \u2013 Chalcot Crescent|journal=Upcoming4.me|url=http://upcoming4.me/news/book-news/review-fay-weldon-chalcot-crescent|accessdate=30 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630171418/http://upcoming4.me/news/book-news/review-fay-weldon-chalcot-crescent|archivedate=30 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{official website}} \n* Rosemary Goring, [http://www.heraldscotland.com/books-poetry/interviews/fay-weldon-on-her-30th-novel.18165685 \"Fay Weldon on her 30th novel\"] (interview), ''Herald Scotland'', 20 July 2012.\n* Hester Lacey, [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/ea3c5c02-b622-11e1-a14a-00144feabdc0.html#axzz21wP6qj8g \"The Inventory: Fay Weldon\",] ''Financial Times'', 27 July 2012.\n* Stuart Jeffries, [https://www.theguardian.com/religion/Story/0,,1865034,00.html \"Lie back and think of Jesus\"], ''The Guardian'', 5 September 2006. Interview and review of ''What Makes Women Happy''. Weldon describes her near-death experience and spiritual journey from atheism to belief in God.\n* Fay Weldon, [https://archive.is/20130505071030/http://www.saga.co.uk/saga-magazine/4-fay-weldon.aspx \"My left knee\"], ''[[Saga Magazine]]'', 10 October 2011. Weldon writes candidly about having her knee replaced at 80, and her fears prior to the operation.\n* {{LCAuth|n50002441|Fay Weldon|92|ue}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weldon, Fay}}\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:Feminist writers]]\n[[Category:English screenwriters]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of Bath Spa University]]\n[[Category:Academics of Brunel University London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Copywriters]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:People from Hampstead]]\n[[Category:People from Alvechurch]]\n[[Category:People educated at South Hampstead High School]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Rubyuser", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar and punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fay_Weldon"}
{"title_page": "Paul Masvidal", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- For individuals; see Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Paul Masvidal\n| image            = Paul Masvidal 2020.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Photo by [http://darrinnoble.com/ Darrin Noble]\n| image_size       = 250\n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Paul Albert Masvidal\n| alias            = \n| birth_place      = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1971|1|20}}\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = [[Miami, Florida]], United States\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* vocals\n* keyboards\n* [[guitar synthesizer]]\n* vocoder\n* electric guitar\n* acoustic guitar\n* nylon string guitar\n}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* {{nowrap|[[Progressive rock]]}}\n* [[heavy metal music|metal]]\n* [[ambient music|ambient]]\n* [[experimental music|experimental]]\n* [[acoustic music|acoustic]]\n* [[New-age_music|new age]]\n* [[Singer-songwriter|singer songwriter]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* Songwriter\n* Artist\n}}\n| years_active     = 1987\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n* [[Season of Mist]]\n* [[SPV GmbH|SPV]]\n* [[Warner Music]]\n* [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Cynic (band)|Cynic]]\n* Portal\n* [[\u00c6on Spoke]]\n* [[Death (metal band)|Death]]\n* Onward With Love\n* Masvidal\n}}\n| website          = http://masvidalien.com/\n}}\n\n'''Paul Albert Masvidal''' (born 20 January 1971) is an American guitarist, songwriter and producer. He is the guitarist, singer, and a founding member of the progressive rock band, [[Cynic (band)|Cynic]]. He has remained a continual member for nearly three decades and has developed numerous other projects including [[\u00c6on Spoke]], Onward with Love, and recently his solo work. Masvidal was ranked in ''[[Loudwire]]''<nowiki/>'s 66 Best Hard Rock + Metal Guitarists Of All Time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/top-hard-rock-metal-guitarists-of-all-time/|title=The 66 Best Hard Rock + Metal Guitarists of All Time|last=Staff|first=Loudwire|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> and 50 Best Metal Songwriters of All Time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/best-metal-songwriters/|title=50 Best Metal Songwriters of All Time|last=DiVita|first=Joe|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nPaul Masvidal was born in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] to [[Cuban Americans|Cuban-American]] civic and business leader Raul Masvidal. \n\n== Education ==\nMasvidal's early years were spent in the Miami area where he studied classical guitar with [[Carlos Molina (guitarist)|Carlos Molina]], and in college, with jazz musician, Dave Weissbrot who inspired his love of jazz, [[Steinberger|Steinberger guitars]], and introduced him to [[Buddhist philosophy]]. Masvidal developed an interest in mysticism and esoteric topics from a young age, becoming an initiate to [[Kriya Yoga]] in his late teens and eventually a practitioner of [[Buddhist meditation]] by his late 20s. Masvidal met drummer [[Sean Reinert]] in 1984 at [[Gulliver Schools|Gulliver Academy]] In Miami, where the duo began making music the day they met, eventually forming the pre-Cynic groups, Crypha and Seaweed. Masvidal's eclectic musical tastes ranging from classical to rock, jazz, fusion, and metal along with a innate passion for mysticism came to inform much of his work with Cynic and other projects. Masvidal wrote in detail about early life experiences in his Mett\u0101 Mind Journal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metalsucks.net/2010/04/07/metta-mind-journal-with-cynics-paul-masvidal-the-bird-outside-my-window/|title=METTA MIND JOURNAL WITH CYNIC'S PAUL MASVIDAL: \"THE BIRD OUTSIDE MY WINDOW\"|date=2010-04-07|website=MetalSucks|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> series, which he published on the music blog [[MetalSucks]].\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Cynic (1988 - 1995, first hiatus) ===\n{{Main articles|Cynic (band)}}\n[[File:Masvidal with Death - Human era.jpg|200x200px|alt=|left|border]]\nMasvidal co-founded Cynic with drummer [[Sean Reinert]] in the late 80\u2019s, having released four demos from 1988-1991 that circulated in the underground tape trading community. Masvidal developed a reputation in the South Florida music scene for his musicianship and attention began to grow quickly around the band. In 1989, while still in high school, Masvidal toured Mexico as a replacement guitarist for the band [[Death (metal band)|Death]], but declined an invitation to permanently join the band in order to remain committed to Cynic. This had many journalists curious at the time, since Death were emerging as an influential and popular act, but Masvidal persevered with Cynic. However, Masvidal returned to the Death fold replacing guitarist [[James Murphy (guitarist)|James Murphy]] for tour dates on the international ''[[Spiritual Healing (album)|Spiritual Healing]]'' tour in 1990. In 1991, Masvidal and fellow Cynic member Reinert were recruited by Death to record the \"groundbreaking\" ''[[Human (Death album)|Human]]''. In 2017, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine placed the album as the 70th greatest metal album of all time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/the-100-greatest-metal-albums-of-all-time-113614/|title=The 100 Greatest Metal Albums of All Time|last=Christe|first=Christopher R. Weingarten,Tom Beaujour,Hank Shteamer,Kim Kelly,Steve Smith,Brittany Spanos,Suzy Exposito,Richard Bienstock,Kory Grow,Dan Epstein,J D. Considine,Andy Greene,Rob Sheffield,Adrien Begrand,Ian|last2=Weingarten|first2=Christopher R.|date=2017-06-21|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15|last3=Beaujour|first3=Tom|last4=Shteamer|first4=Hank|last5=Kelly|first5=Kim|last6=Smith|first6=Steve|last7=Spanos|first7=Brittany|last8=Exposito|first8=Suzy|last9=Bienstock|first9=Richard}}</ref>. Masvidal toured extensively for ''Human'', in addition to appearing in the [[music video]] for ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7j8vUbMmOwM \"Lack of Comprehension\"]'', which debuted on MTV's [[Headbangers Ball]]. After fulfilling their obligations with Death, both Masvidal and Reinert returned to Cynic in 1992. In 2013, Masvidal joined forces with other original members of the Death ''Human'' line up and toured worldwide in honor of [[Chuck Schuldiner]]'s legacy with the group DTA (Death to All).[[File:Cynic, Focus (1993).jpg|thumb|150x150px|Cynic, ''Focus'' (1993)|alt=]]1993 saw the release of the \u201cprogressive landmark\u201d album, ''[[Focus (Cynic album)|Focus]]'' on [[Roadrunner Records]]. ''Focus'' was listed in Rock Hard magazine's book as one of ''The 500 Greatest Rock & Metal Albums of All Time''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rensen|first=Michael|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/best-of-rock-metal-die-500-starksten-scheiben-aller-zeiten/oclc/62273803|title=Best of Rock & Metal: die 500 st\u00e4rksten Scheiben aller Zeiten|last2=Heine|first2=Uwe|last3=Stratmann|first3=Holger|last4=Villalonga|first4=Marc|date=2005|publisher=Heel|isbn=978-3-89880-517-9|location=K\u00f6nigswinter|language=German|oclc=62273803}}</ref>. ''[[Loudwire]]'' writer Graham Hartmann named Focus the ninth best debut metal album of all time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/cynic-focus-best-debut-metal-albums/|title=No. 9: Cynic, 'Focus' \u2013 Best Debut Metal Albums|last=Hartmann|first=Graham|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>. Roadrunner released a reissue of Focus in 2004 as a special collector's edition due to high demand. Cynic took a 12 year hiatus in 1995 after recording \"''The Portal Tapes\"'' demos. Masvidal moved to Los Angeles in the fall of 1996, upon being offered a full scholarship at [[Musicians Institute]], where he also began work as a session musician and composer for network TV and film.\n=== \u00c6on Spoke (1999 - present) ===\n{{Main articles|\u00c6on Spoke}}\n[[File:PaulMasvidalSOUND12-03.jpg|thumb|Masvidal with [[\u00c6on Spoke]]|alt=|150x150px]]\nDuring Cynic's hiatus, Masvidal founded [[\u00c6on Spoke]], whose ethereal indie rock was heralded as \"beautiful, exquisite [and] destined for greatness\" by Janice Long, BBC Radio. In 2004, the band received airplay on BBC Radio 2 and XFM for the single \"Silence\". The following year, the track \"Emmanuel\" appeared in the indie breakout film ''[[What the Bleep Do We Know!?]]'' \u00c6on Spoke songs have also appeared on the Warner Bros. television series ''[[Smallville]]'', ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'' and the motion picture ''[[Cry Wolf (2005 film)|Cry Wolf]]''. \u00a0Their self-titled debut LP was released in 2007 on SPV Records.\n=== Cynic (reunion 2006 - 2014) ===\n{{Main articles|Cynic (band)}}\nCynic reunited in 2008 to record ''[[Traced in Air|Traced In Air]]'', their comeback opus. In his review<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=The New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/01/arts/music/01choi.html|title=New CDs|date=2008-11-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, ''New York Times'' music critic Ben Ratliff wrote that Cynic \"should be understood not so much alongside any metal bands but along with the radical harmonic progressives in the last 45 years of pop and jazz: composers like Milton Nascimento, the Beach Boys or Pat Metheny.\" [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]] described it as \"A Modern Classic.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/a-modern-classic-cynics-e_b_190622|title=A Modern Classic: Cynic's Traced in Air , A Reunion Album As Good As the Classic Debut|last=Remington|first=Alex|last2=ContributorBlogger|date=2009-05-24|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 and 2011 Cynic released two conceptual records: ''[[Re-Traced]]'' (2010), featuring re-interpretations of several ''Traced in Air'' tracks, and ''[[Carbon-Based Anatomy]]'' (2011). ''Rolling Stone'' music critic Hank Shteamer raved in his review<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/16034-carbon-based-anatomy-ep/|title=Cynic: Carbon-Based Anatomy EP|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> of ''Carbon-Based Anatomy'': \"The title track is a perfectly paced stunner...Cynic sounds fully liberated, not just from their metal past but from any aesthetic concern other than assembling a great song.\" The album's opening track ''\"Amidst The Coals\"'' features artist, [[Amy Correia]] singing an adaptation of an Amazonian [[Icaro]], inspired by Masvidal's work with the South American entheogenic brew, [[Ayahuasca]].\n{{Gallery\n| align = right\n| width = 150\n| File:Cynic, Traced In Air (2008).jpg|Cynic, ''Traced In Air'' (2008)\n| File:Cynic, Re-Traced (2010).jpg| Cynic, ''Re-Traced'' (2010)\n| File:Cynic, Carbon-Based Anatomy (2011).jpg| Cynic, ''Carbon-Based Anatomy'' (2011)\n| File:Cynic, Kindly Bent to Free Us (2014).jpg|Cynic, ''Kindly Bent to Free Us'' (2014)\n| noborder=yes\n| mode=packed\n|title=}}\nCynic's third full-length album, ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]'', released in 2014, was hailed by [[Malcolm Dome|Malcome Dome]] of ''[[Prog (magazine)|Prog]]'' magazine as \"an album that transcends all the limitations of genre and era... There are few albums which can claim such a remarkable hold.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/reviews/cynic-kindly-bent-to-free-us|title=Cynic: Kindly Bent To Free Us|last=February 2014|first=Malcolm Dome 11|website=Prog Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The album rose to No. 4<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.billboard.com/charts/heatseekers-albums/2014-03-08|title=Heatseekers Albums Chart|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s Heatseekers chart in February 2014 and was No. 1 on ''[[CMJ]]''<nowiki/>'s Loud Rock Chart the following month.\n\n<nowiki/><nowiki/><blockquote>\"Kindly Bent to Free Us [is] an album that, while most definitely in the realm of prog rock, has the kind of open, unpretentious air that makes Rush such an easy-to-love band.\" - [[AllMusic.com|allmusic.com]]</blockquote><blockquote>\"The alchemy of front man Paul Masvidal (vocals, guitars & keyboards) combined with rhythmaniac Sean Reinert (drums) and the technically divine Sean Malone (bass), make Cynic one of the finest Prog Rock bands to have ever of landed on Planet Earth\" - [https://burningfist.co.uk burningfist.co.uk]</blockquote>\n\n\n=== Onward with Love (2015 - present) ===\n[[File:Onward with Love.jpg|thumb|150x150px|Onward with Love, 2015|alt=]]In 2015, Masvidal ventured into the performing-arts world with masked duo Onward with Love (OwL), a musical collaboration with acclaimed singer-songwriter [[Amy Correia]]. The pair's singular points of view make for an intriguing synthesis of Eastern-influenced philosophy, symbolist poetry, American blues, jazz and experimental rock. OwL has performed in concert venues, hospices and art galleries around greater Los Angeles. In 2015, OwL unveiled a video for the song ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SHrg6W6gddY \"Kali In My Arms\"]'', which was featured in the HBO TV series and film, ''[[Looking (TV series)|Looking]]''. The duo officially released the song [https://distrokid.com/hyperfollow/onwardwithlove/kali-in-my-arms digitally] in 2019 have plans to release a full-length record by 2021.\n\n=== Television and Motion Pictures - Composer credit (2013 - 2019) ===\nMasvidal also writes and performs music for television and motion pictures. His credits include main title (composer credit) on an Emmy nominated NBC teen series show ''[[Operation Junkyard]]'', short films ''The Yellow Umbrella'', ''A Bride in Black'', assistant to [[Ben Vaughn]] and session musician for Carsey Warner network sitcoms ''[[That '70s Show]]'' and ''[[3rd Rock from the Sun]]''. In 2013 Masvidal founded composing collective [http://stillmotionmusic.com/ Still Motion Music] which scored music for numerous TV series on H2, National Geographic, Bravo, ABC and PBS. Masvidal also has a library songs regularly performed on network and cable television. Music writer Jeff Wagner, in his book ''[[Mean Deviation (book)|Mean Deviation]]: Four Decades of Progressive Heavy Metal'', stated that \"any viewer of ''3rd Rock from the Sun'', ''That '70s Show'', ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]'', ''[[Queer as Folk (2000 TV series)|Queer as Folk]]'', and any number of random television programs has probably stumbled across Cynic's core members without even knowing it.\" In 2015, Masvidal produced a children's album for actor [[Jim Carrey]] titled ''How Roland Rolls''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://howrolandrolls.com/the-ep/|title=The EP {{!}} How Roland Rolls|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>.  \n\nIn 2016, Masvidal, along with collaborator [[Amy Correia]], composed the musical score for the award-winning feature film ''[[The Tiger Hunter]]'', featuring lead actor [[Danny Pudi]]. The film was released in over 60 cities nationwide, won the grand jury prize for narrative feature at the Los Angeles Asian Pacific Film Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/los-angeles-asian-pacific-film-festival-the-tiger-hunter-hooligan-sparrow-win-1201768412/|title=\u2018Tiger Hunter\u2019 and \u2018Hooligan Sparrow\u2019 Win Big at L.A. Asian Pacific Film Festival|last=Cavassuto|first=Maria|last2=Cavassuto|first2=Maria|date=2016-05-06|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, and garnered effusively positive reviews from The New York Times<ref>{{Cite news|last=Catsoulis|first=Jeannette|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/21/movies/the-tiger-hunter-review.html|title=Review: A Sweet Immigrant Story in \u2018The Tiger Hunter\u2019|date=2017-09-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, Los Angeles Times<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-tiger-hunter-review-20170921-story.html|title=Review: Charming comedy 'The Tiger Hunter' sets immigrant dream in 1979 Chicago|date=2017-09-21|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, and more. In 2017, Correia and Masvidal scored the main title to CW Networks, game show \"Save To Win\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pilotonline.com/business/article_2428e2c3-f385-5b17-805a-58e61daa7316.html|title=Family Dollar launches &quot;Save to Win&quot; game show on The CW|last=Pierceall|first=Kimberly|website=pilotonline.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.   \n\nIn 2019, the duo composed end title song for the feature film [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lKzGNIk4XBI&fbclid=IwAR2nbrqJe9IjfUrakvWKP7oR6KQIJyRg711IfBCckEqKdKsffbYMBsMmDkU ''The Deported''] which made the official selection at the prestigious New York Latin Film Festival and the [[Beverly Hills Film Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beverlyhillsfilmfestival.com/2019-official-selection-fri/|title=2019 Official Selection Fri {{!}} Beverly Hills Film Festival {{!}} Official Site|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.  \n\n=== Cynic (2015 - present) ===\n{{Main articles|Cynic (band)}}\n[[File:Cynic Humanoid.jpg|thumb|150x150px|Cynic - Humanoid (Single)]]In January 2018, Cynic released a digital single, titled ''\"Humanoid\"''. The song featured new drummer, Matt Lynch with longtime bassist and collaborator, [[Sean Malone]]. \"Humanoid\" marked the first new music from the progressive pioneers since the band's 2014 album ''Kindly Bent to Free Us''. The artwork features a detail from the painting \"Ayahuasca Dream\" by [[Robert Venosa]], Cynic's longtime collaborator and celebrated artist who passed away in 2011. <blockquote>\"Venosa and Masvidal recognized each other as fellow artists in the pursuit of authentic, spirit-based artistic expression in sound and imagery.\" - \u00a0[https://www.martinahoffmann.com/ Martina Hoffman], painter and Venosa's wife, from the book ...''And Justice for Art, Stories About Heavy Metal Album Covers'' by Ramon Martos<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://andjusticeforart.bigcartel.com/product/and-justice-for-art-stories-about-heavy-metal-album-covers-volume-2|title=...And Justice For Art: Stories About Heavy Metal Album Covers|last=Art|first=And Justice For|website=And Justice For Art|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Masvidal (2019 - present) ===\n{{Gallery\n| title        = MYTHICAL HUMAN VESSEL\n| align        = right\n| width        = 150\n| noborder=yes\n| File:MYTHICAL Album.jpg|MYTHICAL\n| File:HUMAN Album by Masvidal.jpg|HUMAN\n| File:VESSEL Album by Masvidal.jpg|VESSEL\n| mode=packed\n}}\n[[File:Masvidal Solo MHV.jpg|left|thumb|150x150px|Photo credits: [https://www.ekaterinagorbacheva.com/ Ekaterina Gorbacheva] |alt=]]\nIn 2019 and 2020 Masvidal ventured into releasing work as a solo artist under the name 'Masvidal' releasing three conceptual albums titled ''Mythical Human Vessel.'' The artwork for the three albums was designed by visual artists Igraine Grey and Jonatan Martinez aka [https://cargocollective.com/greymar/about Greymar].\n\nProduced by three-time [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] winner Warren Riker (Lauryn Hill, Fugees, Santana). Drawing on influences from musicians [[John Lennon]], [[Brian Eno]] and [https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/artist/Elliott Elliott Smith] to visual artists - [[Mark Rothko]], [[Cai Guo-Qiang]], [[Hilma af Klint|Hilma af Klimt]], the songs embrace concise forms and catchy melodies in spite of their often painful subject matters of loss, depression, and heartache. In Masvidal's view, \"pain is not something to be feared but embraced as inevitable and, ultimately, a doorway.\" ''Billboard'' described the work\u00a0''Mythical Human Vessel'', finds Masvidal at his most vulnerable, often with just a guitar and vocals, while experimenting with brain entrainment, a series of pulsing sounds that are said to lead to enhanced neural perception and memory.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8513968/paul-masvidal-interview-brain-experiment|title=Paul Masvidal's Solo Project Doubles as a Brain Entrainment Experiment|date=2019-05-31|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n[[Consequence of Sound]] premiered the launch of music video for the song ''\"Nebula\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/07/masvidal-video-nebula/|title=Cynic's Paul Masvidal unveils video for solo track \"Nebula\": Watch|date=2019-07-18|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. Other press related to MHV: Human<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8532688/paul-masvidal-interview-human-track-by-track-rundown|title=Paul Masvidal 'Human' Track-by-Track: Cynic Frontman Explains New EP|date=2019-10-10|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> / Vessel<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/9324719/paul-masvidal-releases-final-installment-of-mythical-human-vessel-trilogy?fbclid=IwAR3AhHwixQ7LGFZjUtZ1hWW9-ErQ3yH2rH8LZ-k6OsLBmgOGJLyAy0MUqqs|title=Paul Masvidal&#39;s &#39;Mythical Human Vessel&#39; Finale|date=2020-03-06|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nBen Ratliff of the ''New York Times'' referred to Masvidal's \"philosophic lyrics\",<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ratliff|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/02/arts/music/02buried.html|title=From Jazz-Rock Fusion to Progressive Metal, With a Virtuosic Accompaniment|date=2010-02-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> stating that he is \"a musician who can expand his own sense of calm into an aggressive, extravagant art\".\n\n== Writing and performance style ==\n{{WQA in progress}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAs an inventor, Masvidal filed a successful patent ([http://www.vidatak.com/index.html Vidatak] EZ Board US Patent No. 6,422,875) in 1999 (which was approved in 2002), involving a device to assist voice-disabled individuals. Masvidal's interest stems from his extensive volunteer work with AIDS patients, the terminally ill and the elderly in the Los Angeles area.\n\nIn May 2014, the [[Los Angeles Times]] did a front cover story on Masvidal's coming out as a homosexual along with fellow Cynic member [[Sean Reinert]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-c1-gay-heavy-metal-20140508-story.html|title=Great Read: Cynic's Paul Masvidal, Sean Reinert are out and ready to be loud|date=2014-05-08|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. For gay pride month June 2017, Masvidal talked to Billboard about his experiences as gay man in the rock and metal community<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/7842075/paul-masvidal-lgbtq-hard-rock-metal|title=Paul Masvidal on LGBTQ Acceptance In the Hard Rock/Metal Community|date=2017-06-29|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>:<blockquote>\"We were always outsiders as a metal band, not only sonically with our influences coming at it from a totally different direction, but we never wore the masculine badge as being tough guys or any of that. We oftentimes wore very colorful clothes, so we were just a little more eccentric and kind of outside the box...\" </blockquote>In an interview<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tricycle.org/trikedaily/buddhist-rocker/|title=The Heavy Metta of a Buddhist Rocker|last=Strahley|first=Erin|date=2018-11-07|website=Tricycle: The Buddhist Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> for [[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review|Tricycle magazine]], Masvidal elaborated on the origins of Cynic's name, Buddhism and his creative process. \n\nMasvidal has been a [[vegetarian]] since 1989<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/progmetal/comments/2gsxkr/greeting_this_is_paul_welcome_to_my_ama/|title=r/progmetal - Greeting this is Paul, welcome to my AMA!|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nMasvidal began work with his brother, [https://www.dancingshiva.com/about/our-founder Maheshananda], an established and influential teacher of Yoga and Ayurveda in 2018, offering Ayurvedic and [[Cannabidiol|CBD]]-based products with company ''[https://morelifemarket.com/ More Life Market]''.\n\nMasvidal has most recently entered into the creation of physical objects, developing [[Orgone|Orgonite]] related devices and [[Sacred geometry|sacred geometric]] amulets. His interest in [[Cosmology]], [[Consciousness]], [[Extra-terrestrials|Extra-Terrestrials]], [[Unidentified flying object|UFOs]], [[Crop circle|crop circles]] and their connection to his spiritual interests have become integral to his work as an artist.\n\n==Gear==\n[[File:Masvidalien Cosmo.png|thumb|152x152px|The Masvidalien Cosmo|alt=]]Masvidal has been playing [[Steinberger]] GM & GR headless 6-string guitars since his beginnings as a professional musician. Although he was seen by far the most with this instrument, he was also seen playing a Gibson SG with \u00c6on Spoke. Since Masvidal's association with the DTA (earlier called ''Death To All'') tours in 2013, a touring tribute to his former band [[Death (metal band)|Death]] and the songs of [[Chuck Schuldiner]], he has been playing his signature Strandberg ''Masvidalien'' headless 6-string guitar. He also had his recording debut with this new Strandberg guitar on Cynic's 2014 release, ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]''.\nMasvidal lent his name to a line of signature instruments aptly named, ''Masvidalien Cosmo''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://strandbergguitars.com/artists/paul-masvidal/|title=Paul Masvidal|website=.strandberg* Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> produced by Sweden's award-winning '''[https://strandbergguitars.com/ .strandberg* Guitars]'''. \n\n==Discography==\n\n=== Cynic ===\n\n* ''[[Focus (Cynic album)|Focus]]'' (1993)\n*''Focus'' 'Remastered Re-Issue with bonus tracks' (2004)\n* ''[[Traced in Air]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Re-Traced]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Carbon-Based Anatomy]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Portal Tapes]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]'' (2014)\n*''Uroboric Forms - The Complete Demo Recordings'' (2017)\n*''Humanoid'' single release (2018)\n*''Traced In Air''\u00a0'Remixed' (2019)\n\n=== Solo ===\n\n* ''Mythical'' (2019)\n* ''Human'' (2019)\n* ''Vessel'' (2020) \n\n=== Other ===\n\n* [[Death (metal band)|Death]] \u2212 ''[[Human (Death album)|Human]]'' (1991)\n*[[\u00c6on Spoke]] \u2212 ''[[Above the Buried Cry]]'' (2004)\n* [[\u00c6on Spoke]] \u2212 ''[[\u00c6on Spoke (album)|\u00c6on Spoke]]'' (2007)\n\n=== Guest/Session ===\n\n*[[Master (American band)|Master]] \u2013 ''On The Seventh Day God Created... Master'' (1991) (guitars)\n*[[Terri Nunn|Terri Nunn (Berlin)]] (1997) - co-wrote songs for an unreleased solo album\n*[[Gordian Knot (band)|Gordian Knot]] \u2212 ''[[Emergent (album)|Emergent]]'' (2003)\n*[[Amy Correia]] - ''Lakeville'' (2004) (Guitar, Piano, keyboards)\n*[[Exivious]] \u2013 ''Exivious'' (2009) (guitar solo on \"Embrace The Unknown\")\n*[[Devin Townsend Project]] \u2013 ''[[Deconstruction (Devin Townsend Project album)|Deconstruction]]'' (2010) (vocals on \"Sumeria\")\n*[[Gene Ween|Aaron Freeman]] - ''Marvelous Clouds''\u00a0 (2012) (Acoustic guitar)\n*[[Chris Schlarb]] \u2013 ''Psychic Temple II'' (2013)\n* [[Persefone]] \u2013 ''AATHMA'' (2017) (vocals on ''Living Waves'')\n* [[Neil Grant]] - ''Location Persuader'' (2017) (Guitars & vocals on \"Throw me out there!\")\n* [[Contrarian]] \u2013 ''To Perceive Is to Suffer'' (2017) (vocals on \"At Fate's Hands\")\n*[https://stephanepigeon.com/ Dr. Stephane Pigeon] (2019) - ''Mythical Human Vessel'''s Isochronic Tones, Transdimensional Traveler 'Mynoise' player\n* BRVMAK - ''In Nomine Patris'' (2019) (vocals on \"Omnipotence\")  \n* Moon Destroys - ''Maiden Voyage'' (2020) (vocals on \"Stormbringer\")\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}<br />{{Cynic}}\n{{Death (band)}}\n{{\u00c6on Spoke}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masvidal, Paul}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Death metal musicians]]\n[[Category:Death (metal band) members]]\n[[Category:Progressive metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Florida]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Musicians Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Cynic (band) members]]\n[[Category:\u00c6on Spoke members]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- For individuals; see Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Paul Masvidal\n| image            = Paul Masvidal 2020.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Photo by [http://darrinnoble.com/ Darrin Noble]\n| image_size       = 250\n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Paul Albert Masvidal\n| alias            = \n| birth_place      = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1971|1|20}}\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = [[Miami, Florida]], United States\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* vocals\n* keyboards\n* [[guitar synthesizer]]\n}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* {{nowrap|[[Progressive rock]]}}\n* [[heavy metal music|metal]]\n* [[ambient music|ambient]]\n* [[experimental music|experimental]]\n* [[acoustic music|acoustic]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* Songwriter\n* Artist\n}}\n| years_active     = 1987\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n* [[Season of Mist]]\n* [[SPV GmbH|SPV]]\n* [[Warner Music]]\n* [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Cynic (band)|Cynic]]\n* Portal\n* [[\u00c6on Spoke]]\n* [[Death (metal band)|Death]]\n* Onward With Love\n* Masvidal\n}}\n| website          = http://masvidalien.com/\n}}\n\n'''Paul Albert Masvidal''' (born 20 January 1971) is an American guitarist, songwriter and producer. He is the guitarist, singer, and a founding member of the progressive rock band, [[Cynic (band)|Cynic]]. He has remained a continual member for nearly three decades and has developed numerous other projects including [[\u00c6on Spoke]], Onward with Love, and recently his solo work. Masvidal was ranked in ''[[Loudwire]]''<nowiki/>'s 66 Best Hard Rock + Metal Guitarists Of All Time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/top-hard-rock-metal-guitarists-of-all-time/|title=The 66 Best Hard Rock + Metal Guitarists of All Time|last=Staff|first=Loudwire|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> and 50 Best Metal Songwriters of All Time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/best-metal-songwriters/|title=50 Best Metal Songwriters of All Time|last=DiVita|first=Joe|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nPaul Masvidal was born in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] to [[Cuban Americans|Cuban-American]] civic and business leader Raul Masvidal. \n\n== Education ==\nMasvidal's early years were spent in the Miami area where he studied classical guitar with [[Carlos Molina (guitarist)|Carlos Molina]], and in college, with jazz musician, Dave Weissbrot who inspired his love of jazz, [[Steinberger|Steinberger guitars]], and introduced him to [[Buddhist philosophy]]. Masvidal developed an interest in mysticism and esoteric topics from a young age, becoming an initiate to [[Kriya Yoga]] in his late teens and eventually a practitioner of [[Buddhist meditation]] by his late 20s. Masvidal met drummer [[Sean Reinert]] in 1984 at [[Gulliver Schools|Gulliver Academy]] In Miami, where the duo began making music the day they met, eventually forming the pre-Cynic groups, Crypha and Seaweed. Masvidal's eclectic musical tastes ranging from classical to rock, jazz, fusion, and metal along with a innate passion for mysticism came to inform much of his work with Cynic and other projects. Masvidal wrote in detail about early life experiences in his Mett\u0101 Mind Journal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metalsucks.net/2010/04/07/metta-mind-journal-with-cynics-paul-masvidal-the-bird-outside-my-window/|title=METTA MIND JOURNAL WITH CYNIC'S PAUL MASVIDAL: \"THE BIRD OUTSIDE MY WINDOW\"|date=2010-04-07|website=MetalSucks|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> series, which he published on the music blog [[MetalSucks]].\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Cynic (1988 - 1995, first hiatus) ===\n{{Main articles|Cynic (band)}}\n[[File:Masvidal with Death - Human era.jpg|200x200px|alt=|left|border]]\nMasvidal co-founded Cynic with drummer [[Sean Reinert]] in the late 80\u2019s, having released four demos from 1988-1991 that circulated in the underground tape trading community. Masvidal developed a reputation in the South Florida music scene for his musicianship and attention began to grow quickly around the band. In 1989, while still in high school, Masvidal toured Mexico as a replacement guitarist for the band [[Death (metal band)|Death]], but declined an invitation to permanently join the band in order to remain committed to Cynic. This had many journalists curious at the time, since Death were emerging as an influential and popular act, but Masvidal persevered with Cynic. However, Masvidal returned to the Death fold replacing guitarist [[James Murphy (guitarist)|James Murphy]] for tour dates on the international ''[[Spiritual Healing (album)|Spiritual Healing]]'' tour in 1990. In 1991, Masvidal and fellow Cynic member Reinert were recruited by Death to record the \"groundbreaking\" ''[[Human (Death album)|Human]]''. In 2017, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine placed the album as the 70th greatest metal album of all time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/the-100-greatest-metal-albums-of-all-time-113614/|title=The 100 Greatest Metal Albums of All Time|last=Christe|first=Christopher R. Weingarten,Tom Beaujour,Hank Shteamer,Kim Kelly,Steve Smith,Brittany Spanos,Suzy Exposito,Richard Bienstock,Kory Grow,Dan Epstein,J D. Considine,Andy Greene,Rob Sheffield,Adrien Begrand,Ian|last2=Weingarten|first2=Christopher R.|date=2017-06-21|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15|last3=Beaujour|first3=Tom|last4=Shteamer|first4=Hank|last5=Kelly|first5=Kim|last6=Smith|first6=Steve|last7=Spanos|first7=Brittany|last8=Exposito|first8=Suzy|last9=Bienstock|first9=Richard}}</ref>. Masvidal toured extensively for ''Human'', in addition to appearing in the [[music video]] for ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7j8vUbMmOwM \"Lack of Comprehension\"]'', which debuted on MTV's [[Headbangers Ball]]. After fulfilling their obligations with Death, both Masvidal and Reinert returned to Cynic in 1992. In 2013, Masvidal joined forces with other original members of the Death ''Human'' line up and toured worldwide in honor of [[Chuck Schuldiner]]'s legacy with the group DTA (Death to All).[[File:Cynic, Focus (1993).jpg|thumb|150x150px|Cynic, ''Focus'' (1993)|alt=]]1993 saw the release of the \u201cprogressive landmark\u201d album, ''[[Focus (Cynic album)|Focus]]'' on [[Roadrunner Records]]. ''Focus'' was listed in Rock Hard magazine's book as one of ''The 500 Greatest Rock & Metal Albums of All Time''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rensen|first=Michael|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/best-of-rock-metal-die-500-starksten-scheiben-aller-zeiten/oclc/62273803|title=Best of Rock & Metal: die 500 st\u00e4rksten Scheiben aller Zeiten|last2=Heine|first2=Uwe|last3=Stratmann|first3=Holger|last4=Villalonga|first4=Marc|date=2005|publisher=Heel|isbn=978-3-89880-517-9|location=K\u00f6nigswinter|language=German|oclc=62273803}}</ref>. ''[[Loudwire]]'' writer Graham Hartmann named Focus the ninth best debut metal album of all time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/cynic-focus-best-debut-metal-albums/|title=No. 9: Cynic, 'Focus' \u2013 Best Debut Metal Albums|last=Hartmann|first=Graham|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>. Roadrunner released a reissue of Focus in 2004 as a special collector's edition due to high demand. Cynic took a 12 year hiatus in 1995 after recording \"''The Portal Tapes\"'' demos. Masvidal moved to Los Angeles in the fall of 1996, upon being offered a full scholarship at [[Musicians Institute]], where he also began work as a session musician and composer for network TV and film.\n=== \u00c6on Spoke (1999 - present) ===\n{{Main articles|\u00c6on Spoke}}\n[[File:PaulMasvidalSOUND12-03.jpg|thumb|Masvidal with [[\u00c6on Spoke]]|alt=|150x150px]]\nDuring Cynic's hiatus, Masvidal founded [[\u00c6on Spoke]], whose ethereal indie rock was heralded as \"beautiful, exquisite [and] destined for greatness\" by Janice Long, BBC Radio. In 2004, the band received airplay on BBC Radio 2 and XFM for the single \"Silence\". The following year, the track \"Emmanuel\" appeared in the indie breakout film ''[[What the Bleep Do We Know!?]]'' \u00c6on Spoke songs have also appeared on the Warner Bros. television series ''[[Smallville]]'', ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'' and the motion picture ''[[Cry Wolf (2005 film)|Cry Wolf]]''. \u00a0Their self-titled debut LP was released in 2007 on SPV Records.\n=== Cynic (reunion 2006 - 2014) ===\n{{Main articles|Cynic (band)}}\nCynic reunited in 2008 to record ''[[Traced in Air|Traced In Air]]'', their comeback opus. In his review<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=The New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/01/arts/music/01choi.html|title=New CDs|date=2008-11-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, ''New York Times'' music critic Ben Ratliff wrote that Cynic \"should be understood not so much alongside any metal bands but along with the radical harmonic progressives in the last 45 years of pop and jazz: composers like Milton Nascimento, the Beach Boys or Pat Metheny.\" [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]] described it as \"A Modern Classic.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/a-modern-classic-cynics-e_b_190622|title=A Modern Classic: Cynic's Traced in Air , A Reunion Album As Good As the Classic Debut|last=Remington|first=Alex|last2=ContributorBlogger|date=2009-05-24|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 and 2011 Cynic released two conceptual records: ''[[Re-Traced]]'' (2010), featuring re-interpretations of several ''Traced in Air'' tracks, and ''[[Carbon-Based Anatomy]]'' (2011). ''Rolling Stone'' music critic Hank Shteamer raved in his review<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/16034-carbon-based-anatomy-ep/|title=Cynic: Carbon-Based Anatomy EP|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> of ''Carbon-Based Anatomy'': \"The title track is a perfectly paced stunner...Cynic sounds fully liberated, not just from their metal past but from any aesthetic concern other than assembling a great song.\" The album's opening track ''\"Amidst The Coals\"'' features artist, [[Amy Correia]] singing an adaptation of an Amazonian [[Icaro]], inspired by Masvidal's work with the South American entheogenic brew, [[Ayahuasca]].\n{{Gallery\n| align = right\n| width = 150\n| File:Cynic, Traced In Air (2008).jpg|Cynic, ''Traced In Air'' (2008)\n| File:Cynic, Re-Traced (2010).jpg| Cynic, ''Re-Traced'' (2010)\n| File:Cynic, Carbon-Based Anatomy (2011).jpg| Cynic, ''Carbon-Based Anatomy'' (2011)\n| File:Cynic, Kindly Bent to Free Us (2014).jpg|Cynic, ''Kindly Bent to Free Us'' (2014)\n| noborder=yes\n| mode=packed\n|title=}}\nCynic's third full-length album, ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]'', released in 2014, was hailed by [[Malcolm Dome|Malcome Dome]] of ''[[Prog (magazine)|Prog]]'' magazine as \"an album that transcends all the limitations of genre and era... There are few albums which can claim such a remarkable hold.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/reviews/cynic-kindly-bent-to-free-us|title=Cynic: Kindly Bent To Free Us|last=February 2014|first=Malcolm Dome 11|website=Prog Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The album rose to No. 4<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.billboard.com/charts/heatseekers-albums/2014-03-08|title=Heatseekers Albums Chart|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s Heatseekers chart in February 2014 and was No. 1 on ''[[CMJ]]''<nowiki/>'s Loud Rock Chart the following month.\n\n<nowiki/><nowiki/><blockquote>\"Kindly Bent to Free Us [is] an album that, while most definitely in the realm of prog rock, has the kind of open, unpretentious air that makes Rush such an easy-to-love band.\" - [[AllMusic.com|allmusic.com]]</blockquote><blockquote>\"The alchemy of front man Paul Masvidal (vocals, guitars & keyboards) combined with rhythmaniac Sean Reinert (drums) and the technically divine Sean Malone (bass), make Cynic one of the finest Prog Rock bands to have ever of landed on Planet Earth\" - [https://burningfist.co.uk burningfist.co.uk]</blockquote>\n\n\n=== Onward with Love (2015 - present) ===\n[[File:Onward with Love.jpg|thumb|150x150px|Onward with Love, 2015|alt=]]In 2015, Masvidal ventured into the performing-arts world with masked duo Onward with Love (OwL), a musical collaboration with acclaimed singer-songwriter [[Amy Correia]]. The pair's singular points of view make for an intriguing synthesis of Eastern-influenced philosophy, symbolist poetry, American blues, jazz and experimental rock. OwL has performed in concert venues, hospices and art galleries around greater Los Angeles. In 2015, OwL unveiled a video for the song ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SHrg6W6gddY \"Kali In My Arms\"]'', which was featured in the HBO TV series and film, ''[[Looking (TV series)|Looking]]''. The duo officially released the song [https://distrokid.com/hyperfollow/onwardwithlove/kali-in-my-arms digitally] in 2019 have plans to release a full-length record by 2021.\n\n=== Television and Motion Pictures - Composer credit (2013 - 2019) ===\nMasvidal also writes and performs music for television and motion pictures. His credits include main title (composer credit) on an Emmy nominated NBC teen series show ''[[Operation Junkyard]]'', short films ''The Yellow Umbrella'', ''A Bride in Black'', assistant to [[Ben Vaughn]] and session musician for Carsey Warner network sitcoms ''[[That '70s Show]]'' and ''[[3rd Rock from the Sun]]''. In 2013 Masvidal founded composing collective [http://stillmotionmusic.com/ Still Motion Music] which scored music for numerous TV series on H2, National Geographic, Bravo, ABC and PBS. Masvidal also has a library songs regularly performed on network and cable television. Music writer Jeff Wagner, in his book ''[[Mean Deviation (book)|Mean Deviation]]: Four Decades of Progressive Heavy Metal'', stated that \"any viewer of ''3rd Rock from the Sun'', ''That '70s Show'', ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]'', ''[[Queer as Folk (2000 TV series)|Queer as Folk]]'', and any number of random television programs has probably stumbled across Cynic's core members without even knowing it.\" In 2015, Masvidal produced a children's album for actor [[Jim Carrey]] titled ''How Roland Rolls''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://howrolandrolls.com/the-ep/|title=The EP {{!}} How Roland Rolls|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>.  \n\nIn 2016, Masvidal, along with collaborator [[Amy Correia]], composed the musical score for the award-winning feature film ''[[The Tiger Hunter]]'', featuring lead actor [[Danny Pudi]]. The film was released in over 60 cities nationwide, won the grand jury prize for narrative feature at the Los Angeles Asian Pacific Film Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/los-angeles-asian-pacific-film-festival-the-tiger-hunter-hooligan-sparrow-win-1201768412/|title=\u2018Tiger Hunter\u2019 and \u2018Hooligan Sparrow\u2019 Win Big at L.A. Asian Pacific Film Festival|last=Cavassuto|first=Maria|last2=Cavassuto|first2=Maria|date=2016-05-06|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, and garnered effusively positive reviews from The New York Times<ref>{{Cite news|last=Catsoulis|first=Jeannette|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/21/movies/the-tiger-hunter-review.html|title=Review: A Sweet Immigrant Story in \u2018The Tiger Hunter\u2019|date=2017-09-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, Los Angeles Times<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-tiger-hunter-review-20170921-story.html|title=Review: Charming comedy 'The Tiger Hunter' sets immigrant dream in 1979 Chicago|date=2017-09-21|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, and more. In 2017, Correia and Masvidal scored the main title to CW Networks, game show \"Save To Win\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pilotonline.com/business/article_2428e2c3-f385-5b17-805a-58e61daa7316.html|title=Family Dollar launches &quot;Save to Win&quot; game show on The CW|last=Pierceall|first=Kimberly|website=pilotonline.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.   \n\nIn 2019, the duo composed end title song for the feature film [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lKzGNIk4XBI&fbclid=IwAR2nbrqJe9IjfUrakvWKP7oR6KQIJyRg711IfBCckEqKdKsffbYMBsMmDkU ''The Deported''] which made the official selection at the prestigious New York Latin Film Festival and the [[Beverly Hills Film Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beverlyhillsfilmfestival.com/2019-official-selection-fri/|title=2019 Official Selection Fri {{!}} Beverly Hills Film Festival {{!}} Official Site|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.  \n\n=== Cynic (2015 - present) ===\n{{Main articles|Cynic (band)}}\n[[File:Cynic Humanoid.jpg|thumb|150x150px|Cynic - Humanoid (Single)]]In January 2018, Cynic released a digital single, titled ''\"Humanoid\"''. The song featured new drummer, Matt Lynch with longtime bassist and collaborator, [[Sean Malone]]. \"Humanoid\" marked the first new music from the progressive pioneers since the band's 2014 album ''Kindly Bent to Free Us''. The artwork features a detail from the painting \"Ayahuasca Dream\" by [[Robert Venosa]], Cynic's longtime collaborator and celebrated artist who passed away in 2011. <blockquote>\"Venosa and Masvidal recognized each other as fellow artists in the pursuit of authentic, spirit-based artistic expression in sound and imagery.\" - \u00a0[https://www.martinahoffmann.com/ Martina Hoffman], painter and Venosa's wife, from the book ...''And Justice for Art, Stories About Heavy Metal Album Covers'' by Ramon Martos<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://andjusticeforart.bigcartel.com/product/and-justice-for-art-stories-about-heavy-metal-album-covers-volume-2|title=...And Justice For Art: Stories About Heavy Metal Album Covers|last=Art|first=And Justice For|website=And Justice For Art|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Masvidal (2019 - present) ===\n{{Gallery\n| title        = MYTHICAL HUMAN VESSEL\n| align        = right\n| width        = 150\n| noborder=yes\n| File:MYTHICAL Album.jpg|MYTHICAL\n| File:HUMAN Album by Masvidal.jpg|HUMAN\n| File:VESSEL Album by Masvidal.jpg|VESSEL\n| mode=packed\n}}\n[[File:Masvidal Solo MHV.jpg|left|thumb|150x150px|Photo credits: [https://www.ekaterinagorbacheva.com/ Ekaterina Gorbacheva] |alt=]]\nIn 2019 and 2020 Masvidal ventured into releasing work as a solo artist under the name 'Masvidal' releasing three conceptual albums titled ''Mythical Human Vessel.'' The artwork for the three albums was designed by visual artists Igraine Grey and Jonatan Martinez aka [https://cargocollective.com/greymar/about Greymar].\n\nProduced by three-time [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] winner Warren Riker (Lauryn Hill, Fugees, Santana). Drawing on influences from musicians [[John Lennon]], [[Brian Eno]] and [https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/artist/Elliott Elliott Smith] to visual artists - [[Mark Rothko]], [[Cai Guo-Qiang]], [[Hilma af Klint|Hilma af Klimt]], the songs embrace concise forms and catchy melodies in spite of their often painful subject matters of loss, depression, and heartache. In Masvidal's view, \"pain is not something to be feared but embraced as inevitable and, ultimately, a doorway.\" ''Billboard'' described the work\u00a0''Mythical Human Vessel'', finds Masvidal at his most vulnerable, often with just a guitar and vocals, while experimenting with brain entrainment, a series of pulsing sounds that are said to lead to enhanced neural perception and memory.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8513968/paul-masvidal-interview-brain-experiment|title=Paul Masvidal's Solo Project Doubles as a Brain Entrainment Experiment|date=2019-05-31|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n[[Consequence of Sound]] premiered the launch of music video for the song ''\"Nebula\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/07/masvidal-video-nebula/|title=Cynic's Paul Masvidal unveils video for solo track \"Nebula\": Watch|date=2019-07-18|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. Other press related to MHV: Human<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8532688/paul-masvidal-interview-human-track-by-track-rundown|title=Paul Masvidal 'Human' Track-by-Track: Cynic Frontman Explains New EP|date=2019-10-10|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> / Vessel<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/9324719/paul-masvidal-releases-final-installment-of-mythical-human-vessel-trilogy?fbclid=IwAR3AhHwixQ7LGFZjUtZ1hWW9-ErQ3yH2rH8LZ-k6OsLBmgOGJLyAy0MUqqs|title=Paul Masvidal&#39;s &#39;Mythical Human Vessel&#39; Finale|date=2020-03-06|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nBen Ratliff of the ''New York Times'' referred to Masvidal's \"philosophic lyrics\",<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ratliff|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/02/arts/music/02buried.html|title=From Jazz-Rock Fusion to Progressive Metal, With a Virtuosic Accompaniment|date=2010-02-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> stating that he is \"a musician who can expand his own sense of calm into an aggressive, extravagant art\".\n\n== Writing and performance style ==\n{{WQA in progress}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAs an inventor, Masvidal filed a successful patent ([http://www.vidatak.com/index.html Vidatak] EZ Board US Patent No. 6,422,875) in 1999 (which was approved in 2002), involving a device to assist voice-disabled individuals. Masvidal's interest stems from his extensive volunteer work with AIDS patients, the terminally ill and the elderly in the Los Angeles area.\n\nIn May 2014, the [[Los Angeles Times]] did a front cover story on Masvidal's coming out as a homosexual along with fellow Cynic member [[Sean Reinert]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-c1-gay-heavy-metal-20140508-story.html|title=Great Read: Cynic's Paul Masvidal, Sean Reinert are out and ready to be loud|date=2014-05-08|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. For gay pride month June 2017, Masvidal talked to Billboard about his experiences as gay man in the rock and metal community<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/7842075/paul-masvidal-lgbtq-hard-rock-metal|title=Paul Masvidal on LGBTQ Acceptance In the Hard Rock/Metal Community|date=2017-06-29|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>:<blockquote>\"We were always outsiders as a metal band, not only sonically with our influences coming at it from a totally different direction, but we never wore the masculine badge as being tough guys or any of that. We oftentimes wore very colorful clothes, so we were just a little more eccentric and kind of outside the box...\" </blockquote>In an interview<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tricycle.org/trikedaily/buddhist-rocker/|title=The Heavy Metta of a Buddhist Rocker|last=Strahley|first=Erin|date=2018-11-07|website=Tricycle: The Buddhist Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> for [[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review|Tricycle magazine]], Masvidal elaborated on the origins of Cynic's name, Buddhism and his creative process. \n\nMasvidal has been a [[vegetarian]] since 1989<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/progmetal/comments/2gsxkr/greeting_this_is_paul_welcome_to_my_ama/|title=r/progmetal - Greeting this is Paul, welcome to my AMA!|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nMasvidal began work with his brother, [https://www.dancingshiva.com/about/our-founder Maheshananda], an established and influential teacher of Yoga and Ayurveda in 2018, offering Ayurvedic and [[Cannabidiol|CBD]]-based products with company ''[https://morelifemarket.com/ More Life Market]''.\n\nMasvidal has most recently entered into the creation of physical objects, developing [[Orgone|Orgonite]] related devices and [[Sacred geometry|sacred geometric]] amulets. His interest in [[Cosmology]], [[Consciousness]], [[Extra-terrestrials|Extra-Terrestrials]], [[Unidentified flying object|UFOs]], [[Crop circle|crop circles]] and their connection to his spiritual interests have become integral to his work as an artist.\n\n==Gear==\n[[File:Masvidalien Cosmo.png|thumb|152x152px|The Masvidalien Cosmo|alt=]]Masvidal has been playing [[Steinberger]] GM & GR headless 6-string guitars since his beginnings as a professional musician. Although he was seen by far the most with this instrument, he was also seen playing a Gibson SG with \u00c6on Spoke. Since Masvidal's association with the DTA (earlier called ''Death To All'') tours in 2013, a touring tribute to his former band [[Death (metal band)|Death]] and the songs of [[Chuck Schuldiner]], he has been playing his signature Strandberg ''Masvidalien'' headless 6-string guitar. He also had his recording debut with this new Strandberg guitar on Cynic's 2014 release, ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]''.\nMasvidal lent his name to a line of signature instruments aptly named, ''Masvidalien Cosmo''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://strandbergguitars.com/artists/paul-masvidal/|title=Paul Masvidal|website=.strandberg* Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> produced by Sweden's award-winning '''[https://strandbergguitars.com/ .strandberg* Guitars]'''. \n\n==Discography==\n\n=== Cynic ===\n\n* ''[[Focus (Cynic album)|Focus]]'' (1993)\n*''Focus'' 'Remastered Re-Issue with bonus tracks' (2004)\n* ''[[Traced in Air]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Re-Traced]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Carbon-Based Anatomy]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Portal Tapes]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]'' (2014)\n*''Uroboric Forms - The Complete Demo Recordings'' (2017)\n*''Humanoid'' single release (2018)\n*''Traced In Air''\u00a0'Remixed' (2019)\n\n=== Solo ===\n\n* ''Mythical'' (2019)\n* ''Human'' (2019)\n* ''Vessel'' (2020) \n\n=== Other ===\n\n* [[Death (metal band)|Death]] \u2212 ''[[Human (Death album)|Human]]'' (1991)\n*[[\u00c6on Spoke]] \u2212 ''[[Above the Buried Cry]]'' (2004)\n* [[\u00c6on Spoke]] \u2212 ''[[\u00c6on Spoke (album)|\u00c6on Spoke]]'' (2007)\n\n=== Guest/Session ===\n\n*[[Master (American band)|Master]] \u2013 ''On The Seventh Day God Created... Master'' (1991) (guitars)\n*[[Terri Nunn|Terri Nunn (Berlin)]] (1997) - co-wrote songs for an unreleased solo album\n*[[Gordian Knot (band)|Gordian Knot]] \u2212 ''[[Emergent (album)|Emergent]]'' (2003)\n*[[Amy Correia]] - ''Lakeville'' (2004) (Guitar, Piano, keyboards)\n*[[Exivious]] \u2013 ''Exivious'' (2009) (guitar solo on \"Embrace The Unknown\")\n*[[Devin Townsend Project]] \u2013 ''[[Deconstruction (Devin Townsend Project album)|Deconstruction]]'' (2010) (vocals on \"Sumeria\")\n*[[Gene Ween|Aaron Freeman]] - ''Marvelous Clouds''\u00a0 (2012) (Acoustic guitar)\n*[[Chris Schlarb]] \u2013 ''Psychic Temple II'' (2013)\n* [[Persefone]] \u2013 ''AATHMA'' (2017) (vocals on ''Living Waves'')\n* [[Neil Grant]] - ''Location Persuader'' (2017) (Guitars & vocals on \"Throw me out there!\")\n* [[Contrarian]] \u2013 ''To Perceive Is to Suffer'' (2017) (vocals on \"At Fate's Hands\")\n*[https://stephanepigeon.com/ Dr. Stephane Pigeon] (2019) - ''Mythical Human Vessel'''s Isochronic Tones, Transdimensional Traveler 'Mynoise' player\n* BRVMAK - ''In Nomine Patris'' (2019) (vocals on \"Omnipotence\")  \n* Moon Destroys - ''Maiden Voyage'' (2020) (vocals on \"Stormbringer\")\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}<br />{{Cynic}}\n{{Death (band)}}\n{{\u00c6on Spoke}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masvidal, Paul}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Death metal musicians]]\n[[Category:Death (metal band) members]]\n[[Category:Progressive metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Florida]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Musicians Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Cynic (band) members]]\n[[Category:\u00c6on Spoke members]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "Abhaysingh1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated artist infobox - genres and instruments", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Masvidal"}
{"title_page": "Matthew Dolan (footballer)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Matthew Dolan\n| image       = \n| fullname    = Matthew Alexander Dolan<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|22859|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1993|2|11|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman/>\n| birth_place = [[Hartlepool]],<ref name=Hugman/> England\n| height      = 1.75m<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newport-county.co.uk/teams/first-team/midfielder/matthew-dolan/ |title=First Team \u2013 Midfielder \u2013 Matthew Dolan |publisher=Newport County A.F.C. |accessdate=19 July 2017 }}</ref>\n| position    = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| clubnumber  = 8\n| youthyears1 =  | youthclubs1 = [[Middlesbrough F.C. Reserves and Academy|Middlesbrough]]\n| years1 = 2010\u20132014 | clubs1 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]                  | caps1 =  0 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2013      | clubs2 = \u2192 [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] (loan)             | caps2 =  7 | goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] (loan) | caps3 = 19 | goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 2014      | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)       | caps4 = 11 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs5 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]                | caps5 = 13 | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2014      | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] (loan) | caps6 = 2  | goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2015\u20132017 | clubs7 = [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]]                      | caps7 = 77 | goals7 = 7\n| years8 = 2017\u2013     | clubs8 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]              | caps8 = 94 | goals8 = 5\n| club-update = 18:52, 29 March 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Matthew Alexander Dolan''' (born 11 February 1993) is an English [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]. Dolan is primarily a midfielder, but is also comfortable in defense.\n\nGrant Jeffreys is said to be Dolans favourite manager that he has ever played under, as Dolan won three back to back player of the year awards as the two of them shot up the divisions with Newport County and Dolan achieved club legend status.\n\n==Career==\n===Middlesbrough===\nDolan began his career at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and in July 2010 was awarded a four-year professional contract with the club, and was captain of their U21 side.<ref name=\"Middlsbrough profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/squad/academy/0,,1~2313566,00.html |title=Matthew Dolan |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. |accessdate=9 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 4 January 2013, Dolan joined [[Football League One]] side [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] on a months loan deal,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20916289 |title=Matthew Dolan: Yeovil Town sign Middlesbrough defender on loan |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 January 2013 |accessdate=9 January 2013 }}</ref> and made his debut as a substitute in their [[Football League Trophy]] area semi-final defeat against [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20880538 |title=Leyton Orient 1\u20130 Yeovil |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 January 2013 |accessdate=9 January 2013 }}</ref> He played his first League One match for the club in the 2\u20130 win at [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20919010 |title=Sheffield United 0\u20132 Yeovil |publisher=BBC Sport | date=12 January 2013 |accessdate=31 January 2013 }}</ref> Dolan only managed five appearances for Yeovil in his first spell on loan before returning to the Riverside due to injury.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/Middlesbrough-midfielder-Matt-Dolan-played-final/story-18343507-detail/story.html#axzz2OqBIaD2m |title=Middlesbrough midfielder Matt Dolan may have played final Yeovil Town game |publisher=Western Gazette |date=7 March 2013 |accessdate=28 March 2013 }}</ref> On 27 March 2013, Dolan unexpectedly returned to Yeovil for a second loan spell this time until the end of the 2012\u201313 season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21969472 |title=Matthew Dolan: Yeovil bring back Middlesbrough midfielder |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 March 2013 |accessdate=28 March 2013 }}</ref> On 29 March 2013, Dolan made his first appearance of his second loan spell for Yeovil as a second-half substitute in a goalless draw against [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21892113 |title=Yeovil 0\u20130 Walsall |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 March 2013 |accessdate=2 April 2013 }}</ref> On 1 April, he scored his first goal in professional football in the 2\u20131 away win at [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], with a goal scored direct from a free kick.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21921304 |title=Notts County 1\u20132 Yeovil |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 April 2013 |accessdate=2 April 2013 }}</ref> Dolan appeared as a second-half substitute in the [[2013 Football League One play-off Final|2013 League One play-off Final]] as Yeovil beat [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] 2\u20131 to secure promotion to the [[Football League Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22499110 |title=Brentford 1\u20132 Yeovil |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 May 2013 |accessdate=20 May 2013 }}</ref> Dolan returned to Middlesbrough having made 9 appearances for Yeovil in a loan spell hampered by injuries.\n\nIn August 2013, Dolan joined his home-town team [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] on a one-month loan deal, linking up with former Middlesbrough coaches [[Colin Cooper]] and [[Craig Hignett]]. This loan was extended in October.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24303499 |title=Matthew Dolan: Hartlepool extend loan of Middlesbrough midfielder |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 September 2013 |accessdate=23 October 2013 }}</ref> Dolan then scored his first goal for the club, in a 3\u20131 win over [[AFC Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] on 22 October 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hartlepool United 3-1 AFC Wimbledon|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24529700|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 October 2013|accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref> This was followed up his second came on 26 December 2013, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Chesterfield 1-1 Hartlepool United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25442012|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 December 2013|accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref> Dolan returned to Hartlepool United in January after making 20 appearance and scoring twice for the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartlepoolunited.co.uk/news/article/090114-matty-dolan-1283321.aspx |title=Dolan Returns To Middlesbrough |publisher=Hartlepool United F.C. |accessdate=1 September 2014 |date=9 January 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901223229/http://www.hartlepoolunited.co.uk/news/article/090114-matty-dolan-1283321.aspx |archivedate=1 September 2014 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\nUnder the management of [[Aitor Karanka]], Dolan was the among players to be offload as part of Karanka's reducing the squad size.<ref>{{cite news|title=Middlesbrough: Aitor Karanka wants squad size reduced|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25886071|publisher=BBC Sport|date=24 January 2014|accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref> So on 1 September 2014 Dolan agreed to join [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/news/article/dolan-deal-in-place-1344554.aspx |title=Dolan deal in place |publisher=Bradford City A.F.C. |accessdate=1 September 2014 |date=6 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901223704/http://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/news/article/dolan-deal-in-place-1344554.aspx |archivedate=1 September 2014 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\n===Bradford City===\nOn 6 May 2014, Dolan agreed to join Bradford City on a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/news/article/dolan-signed-up-1556259.aspx |title=DOLAN SIGNED UP |publisher=Bradford City A.F.C. |accessdate=1 September 2014 |date=16 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901223854/http://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/news/article/dolan-signed-up-1556259.aspx |archivedate=1 September 2014 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\nHe moved on loan to Hartlepool United on 27 November 2014. He only made 2 appearances when he was recalled to Bradford City due to an injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/11631746.Bradford_City_midfielder_returns_to_Hartlepool_on_loan/|title=Bradford City midfielder returns to Hartlepool on loan|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus}}</ref>\n\n===Yeovil Town===\nFollowing his release from Bradford City, Dolan agreed to sign for [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] on a two-year deal from the 1 July 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33164468 |title=Matt Dolan: Yeovil Town sign midfielder |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 June 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Newport County===\nOn 7 June 2017, Dolan rejected the offer of a new contract from Yeovil to sign for fellow League Two side [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] on a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40189014 |title=Matt Dolan: Midfielder joins Newport County on two-year deal |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 June 2017 |accessdate=7 June 2017 }}</ref> He made his debut for Newport on the opening day of the 2017\u201318 season, in a 3\u20133 draw at [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40761204 |title=Stevenage 3\u20133 Newport County |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2017 |accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref> On 10 November 2017 Dolan scored his first goal for Newport in the 1-1 draw against Port Vale in League Two.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41854498 Dolan scores for Newport]</ref> On 26 January 2019 Dolan scored the equalising goal in the 93rd minute against Championship club Middlesbrough in the FA Cup 4th round 1-1 draw.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46928649 Dolan scores against Middlesbrough]</ref> Newport won the replay 2-0 and progressed to the FA Cup 5th round home tie against reigning Premier League champions Manchester City.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47037237 Newport beat Middlesbrough]</ref> Manchester City won the match 4-1. Dolan scored the winning goal in the 2018-19 League Two playoff semi-final penalty shoot-out against [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] <ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48165959 Newport beat Mansfield]</ref> In the [[2019 EFL League Two play-off Final|League Two playoff final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] on 25 May 2019 Newport lost to [[Tranmere Rovers]], 1-0 after a goal in the 119th minute.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48318580 Tranmere beat Newport]</ref> In June 2019 Dolan signed a two-year contract extension with Newport County.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48725042 Dolan extends Newport contract]</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 10 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=68810\n| title=Matthew Dolan\n| publisher=Soccerbase\n| accessdate=7 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|T